    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Orca ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Did you know that cars can run on French fry grease or that kids in Mexico help light up their houses by playing soccer? Did you know that many families in China power their stoves with gas from human and animal waste? \r
Inspired by what the author discovered after a summer digging ditches in a rural village of the Dominican Republic, this is a smart, kid-friendly introduction to alternative energy sources. \r
In 50-odd pages, this engaging and unusual resource covers a lot of territory: from the story of energy, carbon and photosynthesis; to fossil fuels; to wind, solar, geothermal, tidal and wave energy. It sheds light on unusual alternatives that are both imaginative and innovative. For example,  muscle power versus the internal combustion engine, pond scum versus natural gas, even poop (human and animal waste), and vegetable oils versus coal.\r
Accompanying eye-catching photographs and boxed capsules containing energy factoids and real world stories help bring a timely and complex subject to life. Additional resources are provided at the end of the book for readers wishing to further their exploration.""" ;
    ns2:title "Brilliant!: Shining a Light on Sustainable Energy" ;
