ns2:Book022c89ab-dfab-4466-b954-6b695cdbd440 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jackie Morris" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53240" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2007"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Quarto"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This lyrical, striking myth is set deep in the Himalayan Mountains where a snow leopard stands watch over a secret valley, protecting the village and nearby animals. In an italicized paragraph on the endpapers, we learn that these mountains hide the Mergichans or “guardian spirits,” which were once human and have been called to take animal shapes. Times are changing—soldiers arrive with “fire and fear”—and it becomes harder to protect the valley. Meanwhile, a child sleeps, oblivious to all but the dreamy song of Snow Leopard.\r
Lush illustrations fill the pages in blue tinted watercolours that draw readers into the world and mood of the story. Their fluid, watery lines and realistic depictions of animals and landscape are sensitively rendered in soft tones. Readers get right up close to the dreaming girl and to the ghost cat’s intense face and gaze.\r
Text is saturated with poetic flourishes, adding a dense, almost hypnotic quality: “From the beginning of time, out of the silence, Snow Leopard sang the stars to life.” Snow Leopard ends up schooling the young girl in the ways of the sacred cat, passing on her songs before retiring to the “star-filled sky.”\r
A pertinent fable for our times, it is fundamentally about sacred knowledge and the stewardship of animals and planet earth.""" ;
