    ns2:datePublished "1999"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:MacMilan ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Simple yet evocative language narrates this tale of loving craftsmanship (“The violin still screeched, but not quite so horribly”) and its power for good: “He was happier than he’d ever been. During the day, as he dug tunnels, Mole hummed the music he would play at night.”\r
Richly coloured, detailed illustrations show cutaway scenes below and above ground, as Mole gains mastery with his violin. In early images, the sapling growing over his living room wilts from Mole’s noise; birds desert their nest. Additional story abounds, as images show life above and below ground. The tree flourishes as Mole improves; people gather to enjoy the notes that seem to emit from its branches.\r
The privilege of working hard at a beloved craft is beautifully expressed in the language, as illustrations show the resulting benefits for us all. Mole fantasizes about his playing—perhaps he can “even change the world!” Meanwhile above ground, Mole’s melodies cause battling armies to become friends. The final scene shows the tree humming with music, as soldiers rest together and “Mole played one more song.”""" ;
