    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:MacMilan ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Beautiful Lady Catherine Pinkerton plans to open the finest bakery in the Kingdom of Hearts to sell her pastry creations, a revolutionary idea for the daughter of a marquess. “Baking was a job fit for servants,” her mother would say. Catherine and her delectable confections have captured the attention of the sweet-toothed, bumbling King of Hearts, whose clumsy attempts at courtship fail to stir any romantic feelings in Catherine’s heart. His mysterious and captivating Joker, however, is the man of her dreams.\r
In this prequel to the Alice in Wonderland stories, Meyer captures the quirky, fantastic and at times dark spirit of the Carrollian world. With a Jabberwock terrorizing the town and plenty of witty banter between the characters, readers are kept thoroughly engaged. “‘You must think I am a fool to even consider rejecting him.’ ‘My lady, I am a professional fool. I can say with certainty that you do not have the makings of one.’” Themes of forbidden love and self-determination will appeal even to those not familiar with the Alice stories.\r
An empathetic portrayal of the girl who becomes the Queen of Hearts, Catherine struggles to reconcile parental expectations with her own desires. A strong and engaging female protagonist, Catherine is transformed through the inevitable disappointment of her dreams.""" ;
