    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The ordinary and otherworldly collide in this thoroughly engaging novel of one very bad day for 17-year-old Adam Thorne, and possibly the rest of the world.\r
The stylish narrative structure of eight chapters, or acts, defines the story’s whirling elements: Adam’s sense of loss as his best friend announces her decision to move away for college combined with a going away party for his ex-boyfriend, hesitations about his new boyfriend (“Linus at 2 O’clock”), isolation from his evangelical Christian family (“The Yoke”) and ongoing sexual harassment at his much-needed job (“Evil International Mega-Conglomerate”).\r
A widely varied cast of characters are all drawn with wit, empathy and insight: “Adam and Angela had been firm friends ... They’d nearly died together, after all, which seemed a solid basis. He kind of loved the Darlingtons. He definitely loved Angela. If you could choose your family, he’d definitely choose them. And maybe he already had.” Scenes of sexuality between Adam and partners are also written with authenticity: “But with Linus, there was always a smile. Always. Like a kiss was something enjoyably secret.”\r
Adam’s experience of everyday injustice and social hypocrisy is amplified through an intermittent supernatural storyline that follows the spirit of a recently murdered classmate who seeks revenge (with world-destroying consequences). In the end, Adam finds peace among his true friends, while inadvertently providing a magic key for the spirit’s own release.""" ;
