    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Mikey’s small, suburb-of-a-suburb hometown is pretty quiet, except for periodic invasions of vampires, soul-eating ghosts and now, Immortals. The supernatural manifestations (pillars of blue light, zombie deer and the like) are mostly dealt with by the fringe teenagers, the “indie” kids. Mikey, his sister and their friends have their hands full enough with regular stuff—graduation, college, parents. But Mikey also worries about his sister Mel, recovering from her eating disorder, while his own obsessive-compulsive tendencies are getting worse. He’s in love with his friend Henna, his mom’s running for Congress and there is something mysterious going on with his best friend Jared, who happens to be gay and the son of a demigod (“three-quarters Jewish, one-quarter God”).\r
 \r
With the occult and the apocalyptic relegated to mere mentions in the chapter summaries, more common questions and setbacks are considered and demystified. After all, “not everyone has to be the guy who saves the world. Most people just have to live their lives the best they can.”\r
 \r
The first-person tone is lightly sarcastic and plausibly contemporary (“we all exchange wtf glances”) and Mikey’s way of seeing the world is often funny. His spells of self-awareness are thoughtful and his sensitivity to the details of his world, from alcoholism to Alzheimer’s, suggest he’ll be okay in the long run.""" ;
