    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Papercutz"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This collection of tales begins with “The Red Shoes,” the story of Karen, a poor girl, orphaned at 15. Her great aunt takes Karen in and buys her a pair of red shoes, which come to life and won’t stop dancing. For Karen’s safety, her aunt locks the shoes away, but Karen becomes obsessed.\r
The straightforward text appears in captions. Watercolour illustrations are intricate with an unsettling dark palette of greys, greens and red. One panel shows Karen washing dishes in a shadowed kitchen with small dapples of light on the wallpaper.\r
When her aunt falls sick, Karen retrieves the shoes. Small panels show her languid body unable to stop dancing while a voice says, “You shall dance until you are pale and cold, until your body shrivels to a skeleton!” When Karen’s feet are amputated, the shoes “continued to dance . . . until all Karen could see . . . were two dots vanishing into the distance.”\r
“The Glass Case” features a boy with an abusive father. Small brown and yellow panels are rich with dialogue. “You call that dinner? It’s cold!” yells the boy’s father. The boy visits a museum and falls in love with Molly, a doll on exhibit. Unhappy at home, the boy joins Molly in the display case and turns into a doll himself.\r
Finally, “The Little Match Girl” features a washed-out sepia palette. A poverty-stricken girl lights her last matches and has visions of warmth and abundance until her grandmother’s spirit arrives and “flew up with her . . . to where there was no cold . . . no fear . . . no hunger.”""" ;
    ns2:title "Red Shoes and Other Tales" ;
