    ns2:datePublished "2005"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This story of three siblings who befriend a panda incorporates Zen and Taoist tales. The contemporary storyline begins with elegance and surprise, when Stillwater the panda appears in the children’s backyard, holding his wayward umbrella. ‘“I thought I would retrieve it before it became a nuisance.’ He spoke with a slight panda accent.”\r
Each child visits the panda, who shares a relevant tale. When young Karl remains mad at his brother during his visit, Stillwater tells him the story of two monks’ contrasting reactions to a rude woman, and asks Karl: “Do you think you have carried it (your anger) long enough?” Older sister Addy brings Stillwater a cake, so her story is about gifts. Stillwater tells Michael about a wise farmer, whose horse ran away. “‘Such bad luck’” the neighbours say. “‘Maybe,’ the farmer replied,” showing that sometimes good can come out of bad.\r
Realistic watercolour illustrations portray the main storyline in full colour while the traditional tales feature animal characters in black, graphic brush strokes. This book delivers an inspiring message about generosity, gentleness and letting go of judgement—with great opportunities for discussion. An author’s note offers further information about Zen philosophy and historic background on the stories.""" ;
    ns2:title "Zen Shorts" ;
