    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Clockwise_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Erika and Gianni are “Best Buddies” in a program that pairs non-disabled teens with classmates with developmental delays. Both are thrilled to get cast in an upcoming school production of Grease. Erika, who has Down syndrome, relentlessly rehearses the choreography and songs. Gianni, a talented singer and actor who was hoping to be cast as the lead, makes the most of a supporting comic role. The cast and indeed the entire student body and town are extraordinarily supportive, even when Erika’s legs are “slowpokes.” Gianni, meanwhile, on the verge of coming out, is also well supported. The exception is a group of boys who threaten and torment anyone of a different race or sexual orientation or with a disability. Erika’s quick thinking, along with a well-timed intervention by their friends, prevents a tragedy and brings the perpetrators to justice.\r
The chapters alternate between Gianni’s voice and Erika’s, each providing a first-person perspective that allows insights into their minds and worlds: Gianni comes from a big Italian family, complete with the deaf, cussing Nonna; Erika, meanwhile, tries to balance good cheer with emotional honesty as she copes with her father’s advanced ALS. Erika’s voice is especially well-defined, with abundant literalizations and syllabic pronunciations of longer words.\r
The novel is a fictionalization of participants in an actual secondary-school peer program, the goal of which, as depicted in the novel, is to normalize and celebrate difference.""" ;
    ns2:title "Born With: Erika and Gianni" ;
