    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Bloomsbury ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The story of a quiet Adirondack town and a prison break at its penitentiary is told through recordings, text messages, poetry and letters. The multi-voice compilation, intended for a time capsule, features Nora, whose father is the prison superintendent; Lizzie, whose grandmother works in the prison kitchen; and Elidee, whose brother is an inmate. “I’m sure it’s hard to be new,” Nora tells Elidee, who moved to town with her mother to be closer to her brother, “but if you were a little nicer to people, they’d probably be nicer to you.” \r
\r
Gradually, Nora sees the ways that racism is present her town, and how Elidee, the only black student, is targeted. “Black people are always fast,” a classmate proclaims after Elidee wins a race. “So they can outrun the cops,” adds another. Elidee describes an incident at a community event: “I folded plastic silverware in napkins until some old white lady decided she didn’t want my black hands all over her plastic forks.” \r
\r
A turning point happens when the three girls enter the general store and are asked to leave their backpacks at the counter. “I think she made us leave them because of Elidee,” Nora writes. “I know that’s why. I’m pretty sure Elidee knew, too.” The story centres around the community’s response to the prison break and examines the ways that fear and ignorance can operate under the surface. Lizzie and Nora discover their own racism and connect with their desire to make changes, starting with the general store policy.""" ;
