    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "DisneyHyperion Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Poetic language and powerful pen drawings offer a reflection on creativity. A boy in a fedora kneels on the first blank page of the book: “Sometimes I feel small . . . but then I remember I have my pen.”\r
Evocative language conveys the power of his skill: “My pen rides dinosaurs and hides an elephant in a teacup.” With tender realism, the illustrations make the boy’s ideas come to life. In one image, he leans back to taste the myriad unique snowflakes falling around him: “My pen is smart as a snowflake.” In the next, he’s tying his sneaker, which is rigged up with circuit boards and a satellite dish receiver: “And wears satellite sneakers with computer laces.”\r
But as this book makes clear, it’s not all power and magic. The boy’s pen helps him manage his worries, share his feelings and define his identity: “It draws me a new face every morning.” And as one ink-splattered spread shows, “It doesn’t always get it right.” \r
The book ends with an exhortation for readers to express their own visions, as the boy leans over an enormous page filled with childlike sketches and doodles: “Let those worlds inside your pen out!”""" ;
