    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """When Masha, a spirited teen, sees a Help Wanted ad to be Baba Yaga’s assistant, she reflects on her own grandmother’s magical abilities and history with the famous witch. Her father has recently remarried, and her stepmother does not pay her much attention, as she is too preoccupied with her own daughter, who is unruly. Feeling lonely and at her wits’ end after losing both her mother and her grandmother, she ventures off through the dark forest to Baba Yaga’s mysterious house on chicken legs. \r
\r
Blending a contemporary setting and perspective with traditional fairytale structures, this clever take brings the Baba Yaga tale up to date. Masha is a strong female character who uses her wits and inner resources to navigate three near to impossible tasks. Each time Masha is presented with something daunting, she reflects on different versions of the fairy tale and her own grandmother’s advice and wisdom. \r
\r
Illustrations beautifully capture the action, emotion and adventure. Digitally created images are lushly coloured and have a hand-drawn feel to them. A gorgeous double page spread of Masha leading the children to safety on a golden road through a haunted forest captures the magic of the tale. Written with a sharp wit and flare for voice, the story is told almost entirely through dialogue: “You think shimmying up your bumpy leg was easy, do you? I’ve climbed trees with nicer bark than your legs. You make a pine tree look like a model.” A compelling retelling of the Baba Yaga story through the eyes of a determined teenager.""" ;
