    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Dimple Shah can’t wait to go to Stanford and to attend Insomnia Con, a summer app development program. As far as her mother is concerned, however, college is a way to find a suitable Indian husband. Her parents scheme with the wealthy Patels, who have a son Dimple’s age. When Dimple arrives on campus, her first encounter is with Rishi Patel, who promptly greets her as his “future wife.” Despite Dimple’s annoyance, the two are paired together to work on an app, and they wind up falling in love. \r
This romance novel highlights some of the challenges faced by the hyphenated children of immigrants: Rishi venerates his heritage, while Dimple is adamant that she is more American. Although the text is replete with contextualized but untranslated Hindi, “I was born here,” Dimple tells her mother; “this is my culture.” Dimple is headstrong. She questions authority and tradition—“Mamma often lamented that her first word had been ‘why’”—and her strong will is emphasized by punching Rishi in the ribs and by naive musings on misogyny. \r
The omniscient third-person narrative alternately focuses on Rishi and on Dimple’s time at Insomnia Con, where she befriends her Latina roommate Celia, bristles at the snobby “Aberzombies,” wins the talent show with a Bollywood number, and convinces Rishi to pursue his dream of becoming a comic-book artist.""" ;
