ns2:Book1932ba9a-35e4-4eb9-bf20-920f909ed4ee a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Nadia Mike" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55614" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Inhabit Media"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Arrrrr!” It’s Halloween, but unlike the other girls, Leah doesn’t want to dress up as a princess or a fairy; she wants to be “a very scary pirate.” Luckily, her mom is happy to play along. Before heading out to trick-or-treat, Leah takes a last look at herself in the mirror: “Her mom had bought her a black vest, a sword, a pair of striped pants, and a scary skull hat. It looked perfect!” Only one thing was missing, she thought. “‘I need a mustache. All the pirates in the movies have mustaches.’” \r
\r
After her mom paints a mustache on “her chubby little face,” Leah is excited to hit the streets. She loves this costume detail so much, in fact, she’s reluctant to give it up after only one night. Deciding that “it did not need to be Halloween to have fun and dress up,” she begins wearing a mustache regularly. \r
\r
Cheery cartoonish illustrations capture this cute redhead’s glee as she dons a different mustache for every occasion, each one complementing her button nose. When asked what she’d like to do for her birthday, mustaches in all colours, shapes and sizes float in dream bubbles above Leah’s head like bursts of laughter: “I want to have a mustache party!’” she exclaims. \r
\r
Kids will cheer when girls show up for Leah’s birthday wearing party dresses—and mustaches—honouring this refreshingly unique heroine. Championing creativity, Leah challenges gender stereotypes, reminding readers that we always have the most fun when being truly ourselves.""" ;
