    ns2:datePublished "2011"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Donovan is going to be ring-bearer at his moms’ wedding, and this picture book captures the thrilling lead-up. The text uses run-on sentences to mimic the flurry of activity that precedes the ceremony—Donovan “had to race downstairs and give Sheba her breakfast and gobble up all the pancakes that Grandma served him and slurp down all the juice that Grandpa poured him . . . .” The narrative doesn’t name what the big day is right away, and the focus is on Donovan’s important role rather than on any political message—the fact that it is a same-sex wedding is incidental without being meaningless. Each step of Donovan’s morning involves detailed preparations and instructions, from dressing to driving over with his cousins and his uncle and saying hello to the “hundreds of grown-ups all dressed in their very best clothes,” until at last Donovan hands “one shiny gold ring to Mommy” and “one shiny gold ring to Mama” as the couple “smiled and laughed and cried.”\r
\r
Colourful, expressive and inviting, the accompanying images highlight minutiae and provide narrative sweep to depict the emotions of the various participants: Donovan’s beaming pride, his caring grandparents, the devoted brides and the weepy crowd. The attention to visual detail, from the matching red flowers worn by those in attendance to the fancy clothes and the ornate columns at the venue, makes the parallel illustrated narrative as rewarding to read as the text.""" ;
    ns2:title "Donovan's Big Day" ;
