ns2:Book22626fea-d2d0-45a7-992d-bdadd07b1a8e a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "National Geographic Society" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53088" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2011"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "National Geographic Society"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Did you know a blue whale is almost as loud as a jet engine? Or, that you drink the same water as dinosaurs did? Did you know you will probably take 28 433 showers in your lifetime? Have you ever seen a motorcycle shaped like a hamburger, a dog that can read or a fish that plays soccer? Find out about amazing animals, space vacations, freaks of nature, unusual houses, creepy places, extreme sports and much, much more in this blockbuster compendium of 1 000 weird but wacky facts about our world.\r
Fact-filled, informative text is delivered in short, bite-sized morsels that facilitate retention and make learning fun and easy.\r
Beneath the modern, metallic book jacket, content is organized into nine lively chapters, each tackling a wide array of interesting topics. Its eye-catching design features bold images and snappy font, as well as colourful labels, captions, sidebars and fact boxes. A special section called “Ultimate Secret Revealed” demystifies some of the most unbelievable facts reported in its pages (e.g. how it’s possible to make a diamond from peanut butter).\r
An index and detailed table of contents simplify navigation and information gathering. Whether browsed or devoured from cover to cover, readers will soon discover that truth can be stranger than fiction.""" ;
    ns2:title "Ultimate Weird but True" ;
