ns2:Book231d204a-5e92-4afe-bf8a-45d3a2bca33e a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Lisa Moser" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55735" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“The garden was old and forgotten,” this picture book begins, but before long, some critters come to stay. Each segment in the series introduces a character, such as a horsefly, dragonfly, bee, earthworm, etc., or details an episode in the day-to-day happenings of the garden, such as a peach-reaching endeavour by Big Ant and Cricket. The tone is frequently tongue-in-cheek—consider the ladybug, for example, who “never liked her name. A lady had to sip tea, fold her napkin, and sit very tall,” while this bug “ran barefoot, made mud angels, and whistled through a blade of grass.” Many of the vignettes have diction and form that is redolent of free verse, with line breaks and imagery in line with poetry, while others make use of more narrative devices, such as dialogue, with less structured lines. The characters recur and interact, and their presence, personalities, and adventures bring the garden back to life: “it wasn’t forgotten anymore because they all called it Home.” \r
\r
The watercolour and ink illustrations depict each of the characters and scenes with cartoonish glee: “when Cricket almost blows away in a strong wind, the insect winces and grins expressively; and when Butterfly, Snail, and Ladybug sail along in the creek, their boat is a cup, and their oar, a spoon.” The backgrounds’ sharper lines create a textured world against which the softer blends of the insects seem fluid and alive, and the colours and rich, overlapping patterns have an almost impressionistic effect.""" ;
