ns2:Book263f92b4-c55e-45cc-91a8-b8b53fcc33cb a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Meg Medina" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56107" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book about a best friend moving away is a touching testament to the importance of friendship. Right from the start of the story, the first-person narrator, Daniela, presents the main facts of the story: her best friend Evelyn Del Rey is her “número uno”… and she’s moving away. When Daniela goes over to Evelyn’s place that day, she sees a moving truck “ready to gobble up” all of Evelyn’s family’s belongings, and with them the artefacts of the girls’ friendship—“her easel for painting on rainy days, and the sofa that we bounce on to get to the moon.” Evelyn and Daniela’s friendship is a mainstay in both girls’ lives: they see themselves in each other the way young children do, and even their “apartments are almost twins, just like us.” The girls spend their last day together playing happily, as they do, but their games seem bittersweet to the reader because, after a goodbye sealed with hugs, stickers and promises, “tomorrow everything will be different.” The story, set in an urban Hispanic neighbourhood, includes a smattering of easily understood Spanish. \r
The digital illustrations are lively and compelling, and the scenes movingly portray the closeness of the two girls. One two-page spread, for instance, spans from one apartment to the other, with a string tied from window to window to ferry a doll in a little basket across into the other friend’s waiting hands. The adult presence—the move, their mothers who come get them—is peripheral, and is borne out by the book’s final page: though her Mami tells her not to be sad, that both she and Evelyn will make new friends, the last image shows Daniela, grown up, sitting on the floor with a steaming mug before an open box, surrounded by envelopes, reading a letter from her “mejor amiga.”""" ;
