ns2:Book28492e7f-7993-4937-9d6d-7f00ec180204 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jennifer Niven" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54131" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """After her mother died, Libby gained so much weight she eventually had to be lifted by crane out of her house. Now, still heavy but healthier, and self-aware, Libby is re-entering public life after several years of homeschooling. Jack, meanwhile, is a popular guy who conceals what he’s pretty sure is prosopagnosia—face blindness—a cognitive disorder that means he doesn’t recognize anyone, not his on-again, off-again girlfriend, his family or even himself. After he foolishly tries to tackle Libby in a misguided round of a schoolwide game of “Fat Girl Rodeo,” Libby responds with a well-placed punch and the two wind up in a punitivereparative after-school group. Seeing beyond the surface, they get to know each other and like what they find.\r
High school is a harsh, fickle place and the two main characters embody teenagers’ struggle to define and defend their identity, heightened here by their respective afflictions. The chapters alternate between Libby’s first-person narration and Jack’s, revealing secondary plot lines such as Jack’s father’s affair with one of the high-school teachers, and Libby’s fear of death following her mother’s unexpected passing. Both protagonists are engaging; their observations are wry and often comically hyperbolic (during a basketball game, one player, “the slowest human on earth,” trudges off the court, “and, two years later, he sits down.”) \r
Using a different font, the book weaves in intertexts such as epistolary materials or online research. The result is a complex tapestry of compelling young voices coming to terms with themselves as they discover each other.""" ;
