ns2:Book298c3588-64da-4500-a7fa-ce28bbc256ef a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Roxie Munro" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56883" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Holiday House"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book provides an artful introduction to 21 rodents. From the common house mouse to wilder species like Harris’s antelope squirrel and capybaras, the book offers an overview of a few individuals in this often unloved and misunderstood order of animals. A short paragraph for each species provides some information about size, range, habitat, and behaviour, especially odd or remarkable details: for example, naked mole rats, “expert excavators,” have their lips behind their teeth so they can seal their mouth while they dig. The book also corrects misconceptions (lemmings don’t really commit mass suicide off cliffs), gently anthropomorphizes (male house mice are romantic and “sing squeaky love songs” to their mates), and include examples from popular culture and literature (such as Groundhog Day legend Punxsutawney Phil, and the Norway rat that makes an appearance in the Beatrix Potter stories, for instance). The book concludes with a short description of each animal, a glossary, a list of sources and suggestions for further reading on rodents in the wild, in zoos, and as pets. Note that there is no table of contents. \r
\r
The India ink and coloured acrylic illustrations are realistic and plausibly sized. Many of the animals are shown in a setting typical of their habitat: the hamster is running in a plastic wheel, the muskrat is sniffing around in the shallows and a bushy-tailed wood rat, a species known for chewing through car wires, is shown holding a set of keys in its mouth. The drawings are well executed, and the muted colours and meticulous detail are somewhat reminiscent of old-fashioned wildlife drawings. The endpapers are simple line representations of each of the rodents in the book.""" ;
    ns2:title "Rodent Rascals: From Tiny to Tremendous—21 Clever Creatures at their Actual Size" ;
