    ns2:publisher ns2:Annick ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This fairly brief and very compelling story of brotherly love is set against a backdrop of deprivation, violence and corruption. The plot interweaves the social and political problems of an unnamed city (“You Europeans, you think you know it all. Go back to where you came from and take care of your own orphans”) with the humanity of its most downtrodden: “‘I have something to tell you.’ Kai stood on his tiptoes and cupped his hand around Pax’s ear. ‘Mega lost her penis,’ he whispered. ‘Her what?’ Pax stepped back, amazed. ‘I saw … in the outhouse.’”\r
\r
Pithy dialogue is matched with vivid descriptions, such as when the teenage Pax and his young charge Kai are used to unknowingly plant a bomb among the shiny office buildings downtown: “The ground beneath their feet quivered. It was a shudder, a rattle, and then an earthly vomit sent millions of pounds of concrete, earth and dust up into  the sky.”\r
\r
The boys’ perilous subsistence takes a heart wrenching turn when they are imprisoned—and tortured—in place of those with true responsibility. Officially endorsed by Amnesty International Canada, this important story finishes with Pax’s harrowing final days in prison, and Kai’s rescue from his adopted brother’s fate: “I should have been happy, at the very least. For the first time in my life I had parents. Instead I screamed, ‘PAX!’”""" ;
