    ns2:datePublished "2002"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This is a gripping account of the life of a US soldier during the Vietnam War. Without violence or gore, the language brings readers a visceral sense of fear, aggression and hopelessness, as the soldier tries to survive another day. On patrol: “The weather is hot, but the sweat that runs down my back feels cold.” In a firefight: “Suddenly, there is silence. We are afraid to move. We are more afraid not to move.”\r
Photo-collage illustrations create verdant jungle, rice paddies and hill ranges. Hand-drawn soldiers move past rice farmers; a village hut is aflame. No doubt young readers will have opinions on war against children and the elderly, even while the danger to the soldiers is equally apparent. Against a burning sky, choppers bring the patrol back out.\r
This book is a powerful resource for further research and discussion. The unspoken challenge to the meaning and value of this military engagement are made clear at the end, when the solider writes a letter home, and wonders if his enemy is doing the same. “I am so tired. I am so very tired of this war.”""" ;
