    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "National Geographic Society"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """For anyone who knows a dog, loves a dog or aspires to own a dog, this book is a great-looking and terrifically useful resource. Introductory spreads are followed by a range of sections on dog communication, with the idea of helping humans relate to “man’s best friend” in terms both creatures will understand.\r
The section “Telling Tails” includes spreads on “The Scared Wag” and “The Showy Tail” among many others. The language is conversational and engaging. In small doses, even a young child may be read to from this book. “Yawning means your pup is tired, right? Not necessarily.” Sections such as “Read My Face,” “Hound Sounds” and “Trouble Talk” can be consulted as reference or read sequentially. Within every section there is a “Doggie Dilemma” scenario and “Training Tips” to help.\r
Spreads are lushly illustrated with gorgeous photos of dogs (a tiny caption identifies the breed). Sidebars and speech balloons offer additional access to the main message. “Dr. Gary’s Vet Tips” convey medical information.\r
A wealth of back material includes an index, a fun quiz and instructions for homemade puppy toys.""" ;
