    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Tundra_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Witty and engaging language addresses truth, communication and the perils of homelessness in this novel about 12-year-old trivia-whiz Felix and his artist mom, Astrid. Their tale launches with a bang: in a police station, having been caught living in a stolen camper van. “Our cover was blown. I tried to tell myself it wasn’t my fault. I’d had no choice; I had to call the cops. If I hadn’t, who knows what could have happened?” \r
\r
As the voice of Felix recounts the family’s slide into homelessness and its burdens both practical (“We always try to stop for the night near a public restroom”) and emotional (“I told myself it wasn’t gross. I told myself it was resourceful”), a nuanced picture of Astrid’s precarious mental health emerges: “‘Are you taking your pills?’ I asked her one morning… ‘Had to make a choice this month. Phone bill or pills.’” Meanwhile, school life provides some stability; as do friends Dylan and Winnie and their own eccentric families—all skillfully drawn: “‘I flunked out of Kumon!’.... She blew her nose into a Kleenex. “You think I’m this totally perfect person—’ ‘No. No, I don’t. Not even close—’” The story’s crisis and climax are intertwined when Felix’s secret is discovered, just as he enters a junior edition of his favourite quiz show—and wins the big prize money of 25 000. In an authentic and heartwarming finish, Felix is devastated to learn that his money will be held until he is 18 years old. Nevertheless, friends and social services are able to help, now that the truth is out: ‘the apartment is tiny. . . . But. . . There are no people eyeing us with suspicion. There are no cigarette burns, and no scary sounds coming through the walls. . . . It has a toilet and a shower. . . even a pint-sized bedroom, which Astrid has said will be mine. . . .”""" ;
