ns2:Book369082ce-766d-4e96-8c16-296a97ab05d9 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Meaghan McIsaac" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54911" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Tundra_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Themes of class justice and immigrant rights percolate in this action-packed story set in a dystopian future world. Gifted with mental connections to Shadows who are their counterparts in the future, “Phase 1” Movers Patrick and his little sister Maggie must report monthly to the Bureau of Movement Activity Control (BMAC). Dad lies “Shelved” for life, somewhere in BMAC’s prison; Mom is an activist for Movers’ rights. \r
Phase 3 Movers are able bring their Shadows back from the war-torn future, creating a refugee population and subsequent generations—a threat to present-day resources. Told from Patrick’s perspective, the story uses rich language to convey the prejudice and fear experienced by Movers: “An entire flock of feathery, angry wings flapped in my gut and I pulled my knees up to my chest. BMAC is coming? Coming for who?” Meanwhile, a new friendship with Phase 2 Mover Gabby deepens his knowledge of Moving: “My Shadow and I . . . the connection’s too weak . . . Can’t make me see things, think things I don’t want to.” \r
Patrick’s awakening to his own Shadow makes for rich metaphors: “that twitching, instinctual feeling in the deepest part of every Mover’s gut, that itch we all have from birth, the one we’re taught over and over to ignore. The itch we’re told to pretend isn’t there.” In the end, Patrick’s creative thinking combines with Maggie’s and Gabby’s superior Moving powers to dispatch a powerful, destructive Shadow. In the process, Patrick is pulled to the future, for a closer acquaintance with his own.""" ;
