ns2:Book3737e283-7804-4c05-99bd-61068321f6b6 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jacqueline Morley" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54231" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2006"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "National Geographic Society"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Be prepared for a journey back in time—to more than 3,000 years ago. The map below shows your destination, in the northeastern corner of Africa.” Engaging language places the reader at the centre of the action, in this introduction to ancient Egyptian culture.\r
Under the premise of a job offer for a princess, chapters cover topics such as “The Royal Household” (hierarchy and politics among wives and children), “Getting Along without Money” (bartering and gold), “Opportunities for Travel” (all communities were situated along the Nile) and “Could You Land the Top Job?” (Can a princess become pharaoh?)\r
An abundance of detailed, realistic images include full scenes and spot illustrations. Information-rich captions accompany all. “Keeping fresh at the feast” shows a group of dancers, scented cones of melting wax trickling down their faces and hair. “Ancient medicine” depicts a reclining princess, neck propped on a wooden headrest, cat by her side. (“Plenty of rest, a simple diet and spells three times a day for you.”) “A royal burial” shows attendants preparing a mummy for its decorated case.\r
Back material includes a glossary, an index and a knowledge test (“Your Interview”) with a scoring rubric: “Have You Got the Job? ... Congratulations, you were made for the job … not quite ready for this post, but we can offer you a place as a royal attendant.” For a fun, female-centric look at ancient Egypt, look no further.""" ;
