ns2:Book375b16d2-a692-4484-bf7c-14763a1829be a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Andrea Mills" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54913" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "DK Children"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The majesty of our planet, the wonder of the animals and the ingenuity of humankind are showcased in this fascinating and imminently browsable book, which includes a tremendous variety of spreads that cover topics such as “Pouncing Parasites,” “Festival Fun,” “Weird Weather” and more.. \r
For each topic, eye-popping photographs cover large-size spreads, drawing readers into the material. The yellow waters of the Danakil Depression in Ethiopia look like a scene from another world: “Active volcanoes sizzle inside this desert basin, and sulfur springs emit choking gases.” \r
Concise yet colourful language uses bold type, headlines and sub-heads (“local men risk life and limb to throw themselves from dizzying heights with only a jungle vine around their ankles”) to convey the facts: “Land diving takes place after the wet season, so that the vines will be waterlogged to maximize their elasticity and strength.” \r
Inset sidebars use graphics and additional photography to illustrate supporting information on every spread. On the image of a giant tree swarmed with butterflies (“Marathon migration”), the sidebar “Fast Facts” shows the life cycle of a monarch butterfly, while “Supporting the Species” shows a fat caterpillar munching on milkweed: “Conservationists are encouraging people to plant milkweed at home, to create the habitat the monarchs need to survive.” \r
Altogether, the sheer scope of this attractive book’s topics—“Mysterious wells,” “Fleeting flower,” “Food fight festival” and many, many more—demonstrates that ours is indeed a wonderful world.""" ;
