ns2:Book402c9db0-e9d3-46ae-9119-489cec0b9b44 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Julia Metzger" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54409" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Sasquatch Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """There are themes that appear in both sides of this double-barreled book on puberty for boys and girls, such as pimples (What Is the Point of Getting Zits”), body odour (“Some People Have Noticed That I have a Bad Smell”) and sex (“Why Does All This Have to Happen in Such a Sexual Way?”). Other themes mostly stick to their own side of the book, such as “What if I Have My Period for the First Time at School?” and “Does Food Affect Your Penis Size?,” with cross-referencing to encourage the free flow of information: “(Want to know what they think about boys? See Chapter 12 on the girls’ side.)”\r
Real questions asked by pre-teens are organized in 29 chapters on the physical and emotional changes of puberty. Answers are direct, conversational and reassuring: “The penis is basically designed for the vagina, and vice versa. If this is really surprising to you, join the club! It is for many boys when they first learn about it.” Varied font sizes and colours encourage access to the text. The questions are formatted as sub-headings to allow for easy browsing. List formats (“What I Wish Other People Knew About Me”) and compile thoughts and feelings that will resonate with readers.\r
Colour images and black-and–white spot images illustrate editorial concepts. One scene shows a group of girls in backpacks, hands waving, eyes rolling, mouths giggling (“Why are girls so chatty and strange?”). Another pair of images shows same-sex couples in wedding garb, gazing into each other’s eyes: “Can two people of the same sex get married?” The warm illustrative style remains consistent in diagrams of human anatomy. \r
Altogether, the combination of children’s voices and expert advice make this reference as engaging as it is useful.""" ;
