    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“The woods were very still. And so quiet. Kikko’s footsteps were the only sound.” Being helpful and independent results in new adventures, during Kikko’s solo walk to Grandma’s house.\r
Elegant, pared-down language explores a range of emotions, such as, “The pie box was crushed. Kikko felt like crying. But her father was almost out of sight. So she picked up the box and hurried after him,” and “Kikko’s heart raced. She gathered up all her courage….”\r
Soft-edged illustrations in graphite hues make excellent use of paper-grain texture and warm colour highlights, to create sensitive and magical images. One gorgeous spread shows a new pie, pieced together with slices from the animals’ tea party delicacies: “seeds and nuts and fruit and other delicious things gathered from the woods.” Another shows everyone in a festive procession to Grandma’s house, through the bare trees and snow-shadows of a winter landscape.\r
That rich experiences are to be found in the wider world of independence is highlighted with Kikko’s triumphant arrival at Grandma’s. “‘My dear, did you come all this way on your own?’… “You’re never alone in the woods,’ Kikko answered, smiling.”""" ;
