ns2:Book4d84a5e1-a59e-4902-a2df-bf7f117aac93 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Natasha Anastasia Tarpley" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55551" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2001"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Little, Brown and Company"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A little girl discusses her haircare routine, describes the different styles her afro can maintain and learns how her hair is a part of her Black identity. \r
Using first-person language, this sweet, brief tale recounts a little girl’s experience dressing and caring for her afro: “Mama combs my hair. I sit between her knees, resting my elbows on her thighs, like pillows.” \r
Telling and evocative details convey the ups and downs of personal care, including the nightly process of brushing (“Mama puts the comb down and rubs my hurting places”), the variety of styles (“The beads click to the rhythm of my walk”) and the ownership of her black identity: “Wearing an afro was a way for them to stand up for what they believed, to let the world know that they were proud.” \r
Watercolour illustrations combine realistic scenes and surreal moments of imagination. One spread depicts the girl’s hair winding through a spinning wheel (“fine, soft yarn . . . and weave it onto a puffy little bun”); another melds her cornrows with the sprouting furrows of a field (part your hair into lines and plant rows of braids along your scalp”). Yet another shows her smiling face, surrounded by her afro comb-out as it merges with planet Earth, in a galaxy of stars and planets: “Some days I just let my hair be free.” \r
The story’s dual-purpose message transmits the reality of those who have afros, while providing awareness and education for those who don’t: “Once when I wore it, the kids at school teased me. My head felt heavy and I let it hang down low.” \r
The uplifting ending provides a high-minded affirmation that is thoroughly rooted in childhood experience: “Today I’m wearing it in my favorite style of all: two ponytails that stick out on either side of my head and flap in the air like a pair of wings. One of these days I just might take off and fly!”""" ;
    ns2:title "I Love My Hair!" ;
