ns2:Book4e6f69a0-50ad-41dc-93c7-dafa4b27cdd8 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Katie Smith Milway" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55731" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """When war breaks out in Burundi, Deo is forced to flee his home. He is separated from his family and survives on “dewdrops, wild fruits and leaves” until he is found and brought to a refugee camp. There, Deo must avoid Remy, who “picks fights and bullies other students” but one day Remy and his gang steal Deo’s twine. Deo hides his banana-leaf ball to keep it safe. \r
\r
While the language is not complex, the story is elaborate, with descriptions of the camp, the dynamic between Deo and Remy, and the soccer game that unites them. The reader gets a sense of the camp atmosphere as well as the positive influence that playing can have: “Deo picks himself up and quickly sees Remy standing open. Without thinking, Deo kicks him the ball.” \r
\r
The mixed media illustrations are abstract and colourful with greens, oranges and blues. Some of the clothing is done with collage, while the figures and background are textured by thick brushstrokes. Faces are simply rendered but convey a great deal of emotion. \r
\r
When Remy and Deo’s team wins the game, Remy asks Deo to show him his tricks and Deo does using his banana-leaf ball. Years later, Deo returns to his village and becomes a coach, helping “children learn to play together and trust one another.” The final pages reveal that Deo is based on a real person and that there are several organizations around the world that work to unite children through play.""" ;
