    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Alone and lost, Baby Bear roams the dark forest, asking for directions. His large, moist eyes reflect the light of a full moon, his vulnerability captured through the soft textures of the award-winning illustrator’s dreamy oil paintings. Rich cobalt blues and sea greens convey depth of emotion, while Baby Bear repeats: “Excuse me, dear  & . Can you help me? I am lost.”\r
Set in italics, the animals’ wise, reassuring replies are steeped in symbolism, hinting that perception is key. “When I am lost, I climb a little higher so I can see all around,” says the Ram. “Keep walking, Baby Bear. You are closer than you think. And sing a song—it will make you feel better.”\r
The story of Baby Bear’s disorientation invites those who are feeling lost to contemplate the guiding light of intuition, depicted by the fiery yellows and oranges of the moon. Baby Bear breaks through when he fully connects with his heart. “You are not alone, Baby Bear. I am here with you. You need only look up and keep going. You will find your way home,” advises the owl. Baby Bear replies, “Thank you, dear Owl. I love you,” his dark night finally coming to an end once he trusts that he too is loved.\r
Having swum through the rapids with a salmon, Baby Bear stands on the shore witnessing the sky brighten. “Yes, I can see. I AM home,” says Baby Bear. A promising rainbow appears, suggesting that home was within all along.""" ;
