    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Greenwillow_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Written in first person, the poetic text describes the joys and hardships of polar bears who “know how to hope and how to wait.” Despite their patience, “a bear needs something to stand on.” The accompanying illustration done in watercolour, graphite, drawing inks, conte crayon and coloured pencils, shows the bear standing on a thick layer of ice, peering down a hole where a seal is lurking. The palette ranges from a pale pink and purple sky to bright blue ice, to dark blue water below. \r
\r
“There is not enough ice left to hunt on. Every day there is less ice to stand on.” A series of illustrations show the bear swimming in a vast, iceless ocean. In one, the bear is dwarfed by narwhals swimming below. In another, three giant walruses occupy an iceberg and observe the swimming bear. Finally, the bear is rendered miniscule next to the bowhead whale “whose ancient songs bubble up from darkness in creaks and groans.” \r
\r
After surviving a storm at sea and swimming for several days straight, the exhausted bear finally reaches land. The text hints at hardship: “We chew on kelp and bones and grow thin while seals at sea grow fat.” But the final pages show a mother with cubs and reiterates the polar bear’s capacity for hope and patience. An author’s note explains the impacts of climate change on polar bears due to melting ice and provides information on the other Arctic sea mammals featured in the story.""" ;
