ns2:Book54199b3b-62aa-45ab-bb06-0722314297b1 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Noel McDermott" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54828" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Inhabit Media"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Enter the magical realm of Kiviuq, a major character in Inuit mythology whose superpowers save him from misfortune. In this timeless traveller’s world, danger lurks around every bend, yet, thanks to his connection with spirit helpers, he escapes unharmed. Here, a grandfather character recounts Kiviuq’s close call with Bee Woman, a wicked creature who captures, and feasts on, unsuspecting travellers. \r
\r
“When we were last with Kiviuq, he had just escaped from the tuutaliit, the deadly mermaids,” says Grandfather, setting up the story for his grandkids. He recalls how, having journeyed “for a long, long time without seeing any Inuit or animals,” Kiviuq was first overjoyed to spot a tupiq (a tent), then very unpleasantly surprised by what he found inside: a woman with “eyes, large and moon-shaped like those of an insect.” Earthy illustrations capture the stark beauty of the North, while spooky scenes of sharp-toothed Bee Woman keep the reader rapt, curious about how Kiviuq will overcome his worst fears. “You are going to end up like me if you don’t get away,” warns a skull in Bee Woman’s tent. \r
\r
Kiviuq’s great escape at the end speaks to the powers of expression and to the richness of Inuit lore: he is saved by “a magic song.” Inspired by words like “tuurngaq (pronounced ‘tuur-nga-q’) a spirit helper,” readers will enjoy the musicality of Inuktitut terms, and want to practice their pronunciation with the help of a glossary at the back.""" ;
