    ns2:publisher ns2:Annick ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Jule Ann is investigating the bottom of a cookie jar when “a small lump fell out, bounced on her nose and rolled across the table.” The lump begins to eat shadows, growing bigger with every bite, prompting Jule Ann to identify it as “a Dark.” Her father throws it out the window, but the Dark continues eating.\r
The watercolour illustrations are bright and silly and full of exaggerated movement. One page shows Jule Ann’s father standing on a chair, shouting and pointing at the black blob on the table that is grinning and eating the toaster’s shadow while Jule Ann and her mother stare wide-eyed. Another page shows the Dark “as big as a house,” asleep on Jule Ann’s roof. Phrases are short, humorous and repetitive in a satisfying way, inviting readers into a new kind of logic: “The Dark saw lots of house shadows and ate them up. The Dark even saw some butterfly shadows and ate them up.”\r
Jule Ann uses an uneaten shadow to lure the Dark back into the cookie jar. Once it’s trapped inside, she glues, plasters and ropes it shut. The illustration shows her at the kitchen table, supplies leaking and spilling as she works, her hair wild, her tongue protruding in concentration. Her friends help her carry the bundle to the garbage, where a “truck came and took the Dark away.” The final illustration shows Jule Anne watering a fire hydrant shadow: “All the shadows took a whole week to grow again.”""" ;
