ns2:Book5845abf0-59fe-4b12-818a-2c8962bd13fd a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Norah McClintock" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54330" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Orca ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Part of a series of seven stories about orphans, this book features Cady, a determined 16-year-old who decides to leave rural Ontario in search of a story that will launch her journalism career. She buys a bus ticket to Indiana to follow the only clue to her past: a newspaper clipping with a photo of the gravestone of one Thomas Jefferson. A thrilling, fast-paced mystery ensues that combines racial politics with the themes of identity and origin.\r
Set in the 60s, the story is a snapshot of a different time and place. Cady is relentless in her investigation: interviewing and visiting archives, cemeteries, libraries, the police station and even a nursing home. Jefferson, she learns, was arrested for killing a white man and was shot while trying to escape prison. The more she digs, the more conflicting evidence she finds.\r
The narrative is observation-based and action-driven. “I looked in exasperation at the piles of Ledgers. It didn’t seem possible that the local newspaper had neglected such a big event. That’s when I noticed that the stack of papers for 1947 was half the size of the ones for other years.”\r
Racial tensions are fiercely present but foreign to Cady. “They think if one race gets something, then the other loses,” says a local. Despite threats, Cady continues to search. Her quest to solve the crime parallels her search for her own origins; the closer she gets, the more questions she raises about the crime, and who she is.""" ;
    ns2:title "My Life Before Me" ;
