ns2:Book599bb4f2-e8ca-4531-9968-339782f41b05 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Kirsty (ed.) Murray" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54271" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A variety of South Asian and Australian writers and artists team up to offer this collection of brief, speculative stories—both prose and comics—to address gender roles, social equity and the environmental issues we face today. For example, in “Swallow the Moon,” by Kate Constable and Priya Kurian, a coming-of-age ritual for girls symbolizes a new start—and past regrets—in a post-apocalyptic world. The consequences of agri-business practices are explored in Anita Roy’s “Cooking Time,” in which 15-year-old Mandy competes in a reality show that travels through the past.\r
Vivid language brings stories alive, such as Samhita Arni’s “Cast Out,” about a world where only men may practise magic (“I could see schools of fish writhing in the water where the scorching rain fell. Green ribbons of flame twisted through the ocean”) and Alyssa Brugman’s “Weft,” which reflects on the costs of our beauty culture: “… stretch the skin across our bones like canvas over a frame? Then we find a graphic that matches who we think we would like to be, and ink that on our hide.”\r
A stylish range of monochrome artwork portrays the collection’s six graphic tales. Soft-toned images merge cellular forms with galaxies, in the dreamlike “Appetite” by Amruta Patil. Expressive, high-contrast images portray the adventures of “Anarkali” (by Annie Zaidi and Mandy Ord) as she fights social convention for love and freedom. \r
Personal notes from the contributors complete this thought-provoking collection.""" ;
