    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Nancy Paulsen Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Appealing and artful illustrations convey a lively, cartoon-like spirit for this how-to tale of spending money thoughtfully and wisely—as Sonny the rabbit chooses how to spend his weekly allowance of three carrots. \r
“I want to buy EVERYTHING!” “Everything?” “Yes, EVERYTHING!” Clear and humorous language delivers the story through dialogue between Sonny (clutching his allowance jar, bristling with carrots) and his mom, as she rakes leaves in the yard. Handwritten, pencil-lettering adds warmth and expression to Mom’s reasoned speech and Sonny’s exclamations: “I don’t want to THINK! I want to SPEND!” \r
Illustrations with thick lines and vibrant colours construct minimal scenes with spot images. One picture shows Sonny against a giant chart on ledger paper, as he works out his shopping expenses. (“I have 3 carrots. I want 3 things. So why do I have to choose?”) Another shows Mom and Sonny admiring the bouncy castle on Sonny’s list; the following spread shows the ledger again—with 100 carrots sketched inside its lines. (“That’s ridiculous! . . . forget the bouncy castle.”) \r
Altogether, this simple tale offers fun opportunities for discussion about consumerism and wise spending choices—as Sonny enjoys his new purchase of a pogo stick: “And I LOVE it! Boing, boing, boing.”""" ;
