    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In this story, the theme of true value is conveyed with abundant, eloquent narration and lively dialogue. Captain Cat is ridiculed by other traders because of his passion for collecting cats. But when he sails to an unknown island plagued by rats, the Queen offers him treasure for his cats: “let me tell you, it was the cats themselves who had the final say … they had been living on that little ship too long … they refused to go back on board.”\r
Illustrations of charming characters include a fat Captain and a child Queen with an unruly mop of hair. Detailed line work depicts sailing ships and coastal landscapes, expertly coloured as if through a haze of morning light. One image shows the Queen—accompanied by goats—bringing her reward to subsequent traders, who hope for jewels such as Captain Cat received. Another shows the “disgusted” traders giving their reward of kittens to an eager Captain Cat.\r
When Captain Cat returns to the island for good, the final spread offers a stunning panorama, enriched by friends—and of course cats: “surrounded by his cats and his cats’ cats and, later on, his cats’ cats’ cats, Captain Cat lived happily ever after.”""" ;
