ns2:Book60636693-008f-4706-9a5e-391a529b5636 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Kate Messner" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54078" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2009"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Bloomsbury ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Gianna has a lot going on. She needs to finish a science project about local trees in order to be allowed to participate in an upcoming cross-country running competition; she’s not sure if things are getting romantic between her and her long-time friend Zig; her nemesis Bianca thwarts her at every turn and her live-in grandmother is acting weird.\r
\r
Narrated in Gianna’s funny first-person present voice, this rich novel is full of detail about Vermont in the fall and Gianna’s life in an Italian food-motivated household that doubles as a funeral home. \r
\r
Readers will champion Gianna’s efforts to be organized and her logic that sometimes gets her into tricky situations. “I hop onto the counter and lean out ... Mrs. Loring’s shrill voice scares me so much I forget to hold on with my legs, and I tip over backward right out the window. I land on my back staring up at the bright October sun, shining through the leaves left on the lilac bush.” \r
\r
The book shows that different people deal with something as devastating as Nonna’s Alzheimer’s disease in different ways, from Gianna’s mom’s denial to Gianna’s own outpouring of emotion. “She still looks confused, and somehow, it makes me a little angry. I want her to tie her shoe and fix her hair.” \r
\r
Gianna is finally able to submit a science project that’s all her own, and although things are left open-ended with her grandmother’s health, the family is united in their resolve to make the best of it, each in their own way.""" ;
