    ns2:publisher ns2:Tundra_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This fun book is told in the voice of 12-year-old Ambrose, an annoying yet lovable oddball who’s so badly bullied at school, he starts correspondence schooling.\r
Characters and relationships are beautifully conveyed through Ambrose’s keen eyes, whether he’s interacting with his bullies, struggling for independence from his mother, seeking friendship with the ex-con who lives upstairs or reflecting on himself. “Okay, so I’d experimented with the truth. But being honest about myself hadn’t exactly worked for me at other schools, so I’d decided I’d try something new this time.”\r
Strong writing creates an authentic portrait of an intelligent social misfit, while portraying themes of self-discovery and self-empowerment—and showing Ambrose’s ability to affect positive change in the lives of those he loves. Through captivating (and even suspenseful) scenes, neighbour Cosmo finally shakes his past to get the girl, while Mom learns to trust and let go.\r
The book’s Scrabble motif allows for interesting word play in every chapter heading (“re, red, mud, drum, rude, reed … MURDERER”) and underlines the love of language so evident in the crafting of this story.""" ;
