    ns2:publisher ns2:Bloomsbury ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This book offers history students a new perspective on a classic theme. The Lewis and Clark expedition across the northwestern United States is imagined from the perspective of Sacajawea, their famed Native guide, and the lesser known York, Clark’s slave. Key events of the journey take on a new slant, as told by the only two party members not there by free choice. “Sacajawea belongs to Charbonneau, like I belong to Cap’n.” Young readers may be encouraged to find more examples where historic voices have been lost or silenced.\r
Detailed illustrations in rich, painted colours provide readers with a vivid picture of the explorers, the land and the varied cultures they meet. The tale ends with an historic acknowledgement of the slaves’ critical contribution to the expedition’s success, when they are both asked to participate in a vote on the Pacific Ocean coast: “For this one moment we are free.”\r
An afterword offers more information about these two historic figures, a note on pronunciation and suggestions for further research. The endpapers consist of a map, showing the routes the party took across the USA.""" ;
