ns2:Book6956e264-fc42-4351-a186-6ff68d8e2030 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Wendy Meddour" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53397" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Quarto"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Rapunzel is not doing well. Holed up on the 16th floor of her city apartment, she spends her days growing her hair and refusing visitors. When the milkman arrives, he calls up: “The lift is not working, the stairs are too steepmy asthma is bad and my heart is too weak.” But his appeal does not move her. The postman, the baker, her aunt and a rather slick, leather-sporting, scooter-riding prince similarly can do nothing to shift her from her funk. Finally, the gang—minus the prince, who is long gone—decides to brave the 15 flights of stairs, cook her dinner and deliver the postman’s letter. Tucked inside the envelope is a job offer at the local library, reinvigorating Rapunzel. She finds purpose and all kinds of knowledge. \r
Text is lively and full of punch. Rhyming stanzas make for fun, enticing rhythms, filled with contemporary detail. Rapunzel starts her new job with vim: “She put on a suit and a pair of smart shoes,and ate a big breakfast while reading the news.”\r
Quirky and energetic illustrations use a combination of drawing, printmaking and digital techniques. Rapunzel’s wild, wiry red hair features prominently alongside a multicultural cast of characters. Layouts bustle with an energy that matches the storytelling.\r
This update on a classic fairy tale celebrates a strong female character finding her way in the world: “Don’t just wait and sit and stare … when there’s more to life than growing your hair!”""" ;
    ns2:title "How the Library (Not the Prince) Saved Rapunzel" ;
