    ns2:reviewBody "Every Saturday, a young boy goes to art class at the museum where he learns about what makes art, art. “Can you tell me why you think this is in the museum?” the teachers asks. The responses are as varied as the works: “Because it’s beautiful,” “Because it’s different,” “Because it comes from far away,” “Because it makes me feel good.” The boy realizes that his grandma also fits these criteria. The illustrations are done in pen and ink and watercolour. The figures are cartoony but the scenes are full of detail. The first page features the boy climbing the steps of the Metropolitan Museum waving to his grandma. There are dozens of people coming and going, talking on the phone, reading, taking pictures. The museum is grandiose with tall columns and arches. Paintings by Monet and Van Gogh are displayed in vivid colors. Much of the text is dialogue, portrayed through speech bubbles. The students are ethnically diverse, including the main character who is African American. There are humorous moments, a page featuring Picasso who “liked to paint in his underwear,” which raises the question: “I wonder if underwear could be in an art exhibit?” When the boy asks the curator if he can donate his grandma, he replies, “We do not take grandmas.” So the boy decides to feature his grandma in his paintings for the class exhibition. A heartwarming tale about art, inspiration and a boy’s admiration for his grandma." ;
