ns2:Book72c8bf4d-1d3b-42d0-abcb-69b7fb865b9f a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jackie Morris" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53732" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Quarto"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Every 50 years, hares gather in the woods where the males sing to the queen to try to win her heart. One human family raises leverets (baby hares) and is charged with keeping the secret of the song of the golden hare. The family’s little boy longs to hear the hare-song.\r
One morning, when the boy spies all the hares taking off at once, he and his sister follow them and listen to their singing. “He listened with his ears and he listened with his heart and he longed to find each song in the strings of his harp.” The children are pleased that the hare that wins the queen’s heart is one their grandfather saved, “small and ragged of ear, a vagabond runt of a creature.” The children stay the summer to watch over the new family of hares. Their job is to protect the new queen and make sure the old queen travels safely to the Island of the Golden Hares.\r
Unbeknownst to the siblings, they are followed by someone with greedier intent, but as the hunter and his hounds approach, the children begin to sing. Their song stops the malefactor in his tracks.\r
This fanciful tale unfolds in simple scenes, opposing good and evil, darkness and light, as the children of the chosen family help the magic animals fulfill their quest.\r
The realistic, lush watercolour illustrations, spanning two pages, show windswept landscapes and long strokes of shoreline. The hares and their family can be seen as emblematic of the unknown and of the time between dusk and dawn.""" ;
