    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This story, told in free verse, is about eating disorders and body-image issues, as 15-year-old Ivy struggles with her parent’s divorce, her older brother moving out, her mother’s depression and her best friend’s transformation since returning from a summer in Paris: I love that numbers never change.Given two unknown variablesAnd two equationsThere is always a solution.Numbers neverdecide one day They areJust not working.\r
\r
While Ivy’s interest in math provides a leitmotif throughout the book, vivid language relates turmoil over her changing body (“this shape I makehardly fits here anymore”) and her unfortunate coping mechanisms: I stick my finger down my throat,try to erase myself erasewhat I’ve done.\r
\r
The story also offers insight into other sources of teen stress, such as the dawning comprehension of parental inadequacies, concern for one’s future and wanting to fit in. An episode of alcohol poisoning, as experienced by Ivy’s best friend, broadens the book’s message of self-care. By the end, hospitalization for a broken arm reveals Ivy’s systemic imbalances, leading to help for physical and emotional recovery—and a renewed connection with her mother, her best friend and her studies: But try not to put too much pressure on yourself.Math is something you love, right? ... How about we keep it that way?I smile.""" ;
