ns2:Book77340901-61f7-443d-a14a-9d3ba0cf9507 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Andy Mulligan" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53664" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2010"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The voices of three young teens, a priest and a tourist-turned-social-worker, newspaper accounts and more relate this mystery set in a world of near-unimaginable deprivation and injustice. Young teens Raphael, Gardo and Rat eke out a living from the massive garbage dump that is their home.\r
The language offers vivid and eye-opening details about the Behala dump’s shanty homes, the mission school and the hostile world beyond: “The man shook his head. ‘You stink of it. And of garbage.’ He turned away from me.… ‘Boy that’s all you are. You are a piece of garbage. What are you?’ ‘Sorry sir, garbage sir.’ I whispered it.”\r
But the boys have a chance to change their fates when Raphael’s trash-hook finds a bag with money, a map, a coded message and a key: “With the right key, you can bust the door wide open. Because nobody’s going to open it for you.”\r
Determination, cleverness and bravery characterize the boys’ approach, while surviving a vicious interrogation by police (“held just by one ankle … a long way down below me I could see a stone floor”), manipulating authorities (“Just to say to Sister Olivia that I am sorry for what I did”), gaining access to a prisoner (“I looked up and saw that these cages were stacked three high, with ladders up the sides”) and robbing a grave on the Day of the Dead. There are abundant opportunities for discussion about power, corruption and social justice as, step by step, the teens solve the mystery—and ultimately share their newfound riches with the impoverished of Behala.""" ;
