ns2:Book7c226f17-9464-4ae0-8ace-5ea678871a08 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Lauren Myracle" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53657" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2009"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Sophomore Carly looks forward to her sister Anna joining her in high school as a freshman, until Anna’s blossoming body makes her instantly famous. Other things that bother Carly are the attitudes of her wealthy parents and the privileged students at her Christian private prep school. As Carly examines her spirituality, values, changing friendships and feelings, Anna encounters her own problems. But their sisterly bond is stretching thin. A house party of uninvited guests and a dive off the high board in PE class bring them close again, while opening Carly’s eyes to some of her own insensitivities.\r
This lively novel explores profound topics, such as Christianity and spirituality, the social and economic class divide, disrespect for women’s bodies and sexuality, and the complicated bonds among family members.\r
Carly’s sense of alienation is conveyed with wit and style: “‘Yes, thanks for that,’” I say to Chelsea, who’s the third person to make the you-must-have-wanted-to-kill-your-stylist remark. ‘And my stylist has a degenerative nerve disease. It’s very sad.’” The narrative pinpoints social hypocrisies with the relish of an astute teen: “When guys ogle Anna they’re thinking, Dude. Sexilicious. When girls ogle her, they’re thinking, Slut.” \r
Convincing supporting characters add depth and dimension to Carly’s perspective, including new friend Vonzelle (one of the few black kids at school), status-crazed Dad (whose custom shoes take weeks to make) and the steady Roger—all of whom help Carly turn her piercing gaze on her own foibles and imperfections, for a nuanced finish that is enjoyably heartwarming.""" ;
