    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic_Canada ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Jillian goes out in her brand-new ribbon dress. This exuberant story leads Jillian through a series of encounters with frantic members of a wedding party—all trying to find the church: “I’m late, I’m lost! I’m late, I’m lost!”\r
The groom needs laces for his shoes; the bride’s hair is a mess. Everyone receives aid and directions from Jillian, until all her ribbons are gone (and her family shed is empty of means of transportation.)\r
Fun, bright illustrations reflect the lighthearted tone of the language. In one image, Jillian’s mother raises her arms in dismay on seeing Jillian in her wrecked dress. The next shows Jillian being barred from the church (its lawn littered with wagon, skateboard, bicycle and scooter, all loaned by Jillian.)\r
Children may not share Jillian’s composure at the injustice, as she offers best wishes to the passing bride and groom (both resplendent in her ribbons). Readers will be satisfied when her kindness and generosity are valued over genteel appearance: “Hhhhuuummm,” said the bride. “Yes, we definitely need a flower girl.” In the end, a dishevelled Jillian leads the wedding procession, with a gorgeous smile on her face.""" ;
