    ns2:datePublished "2008"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Annick ;
    ns2:reviewBody """At school, Kitino Jacob and his friends feel safe from the marauding rebels of the Lord’s Resistance Army. Yet one night, the LRA breaches the seminary’s security and kidnaps the students. The children witness unimaginable violence and face unspeakable hunger and physical pain; the LRA methodically breaks their spirits and bodies. Jacob, knowing that “we have to stay together,” tries to bolster the morale of his friends: Hannah, who was tortured by the rebels for trying to flee and 10-year-old Norman. The children manage to carry off a perilous escape, but their return to their communities highlights the taint of misunderstanding and ostracism that hangs over former child soldiers and the scars they will carry forever.\r
The third-person point of view affords a young privileged boy’s perspective on horrors only whispered about: as a cult constructed around its leader, the LRA has been terrorizing countries in central Africa and is responsible for abduction, murder, torture, child-sex slavery and forcing children to perpetrate hostilities. The vivid, fast-paced narrative ultimately ends relatively well for the novel’s protagonist, but his fictional summation is a reminder that similar stories of the estimated 60,000 children abducted by the LRA seldom have happy endings.\r
The book includes a note by the founder of the GuluWalk peace campaign and a short glossary of Acholi terms.""" ;
