ns2:Book7eae3250-4219-4124-9bd8-dc74a225e403 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Patrick McDonnell" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55357" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2011"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Little, Brown and Company"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Each of us makes a difference,” reads a motivational message at the back of this book. “We cannot live through a single day without making an impact on the world around us—and we have a choice as to what sort of difference we make,” says anthropologist, primatologist, and activist Jane Goodall. \r
\r
This delightful biography focuses on Goodall’s childhood, and the dreams and events that shaped her destiny as one of the world’s foremost experts on chimpanzees. Readers learn how, as a girl, “Jane had a stuffed toy chimpanzee named Jubilee,” which she cherished and carried everywhere. They discover how she developed her scientific eye right in her own backyard thanks to her gift for observation and love for the outdoors. \r
\r
Illustrations done in India ink and soft-toned watercolours evoke tenderness, capturing the girl’s special connection with nature. “It was a magical world full of joy and wonder, and Jane felt very much a part of it,” reads a heartwarming spread, depicting Jane and Jubilee lying spread-eagle in the grass, smiling up at the sky. Photos of Jane, along with childhood drawings and puzzles, add to the book’s authenticity, while ornamental engravings from the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries add a touch of elegance to the book’s design. \r
\r
Readers can learn more about Goodall’s fascinating career and ongoing mission thanks to a biographical page at the back of the book. They’ll close this biography empowered with information that helps them take positive action of their own, contributing to conservation.""" ;
