    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Daria and her friends call themselves The Authentics—they were “more concerned with being who they were than with who others wanted them to be.” The group includes a couple of different ethnicities—Daria is Persian, and her friend Joy is Nigerian—but they’re also regular California teens, concerned with going out, first kisses and sweet-sixteen parties. Daria has recently distanced herself from girls she refers to as “Nose Jobs”—Persian girls for whom artifice trumps authenticity. But her parents, Pasha and Sheila, nonetheless insist on inviting the whole Iranian community to Daria’s upcoming birthday, and indeed Daria feels very connected to her culture. When she learns that she also has Mexican heritage, she starts digging further and finds out that she was adopted, and that her birth mother is the stepmother of the boy she has been dating.\r
The social complications of high school are sufficiently complex, but Daria must also contend with her sudden new identity. The novel relies on dialogue to provide an almost filmic perspective of Daria’s interactions, while the first-person narrative offers a glimpse of her eye-rolling adolescence and her struggle to learn who she is. Text messages are printed in a different font and capture the electronic lingo of Daria’s generation: “Makes an ass outta U + me. Or just me,” an apologetic message reads. The adolescent vernacular and the rhythm of the dialogue are plausibly young, and, despite her shifting sense of identity, Daria and her friends navigate their multicultural society and its complex referents with ease.""" ;
