ns2:Book857e3cc8-5648-456c-a897-5d8919eab4e1 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Barbara Nickel" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54532" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Red_Deer_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Paired with beautiful watercolour paintings, this stunning poem flows from page to page as freely as the wind. “Where do you live?” the boy narrator asks, while the wind reacts in rich, rhyming verse: “And the wind up high in the flag shivered,the wind down low in the grass riveredover his toes to scatter the leaves.”\r
Starting in the Prairies, the wind and the boy travel to South America, South Africa and on to the Middle East before journeying back home. Along the way, the boy learns the wind’s many names and powers. In South America, the wind answers to “Papagayo.” stirring and churning the sea “where algae bloomed like tiny starsfrom feasting on cold water’s storesof healthy food.” In Cape Town, “the Cape Doctor” clears smog, while in war-torn Iraq “Shamal” reminds readers of the wind’s own sentience: “I’m hit each time they firethrough me, the moving air.I hurt, I heara boy your age crying in fear.”\r
Explanations for the wind’s names, like “Chinook,” are provided at the back of the book, along with a glossary. From cover to cover, the wind’s dance is depicted with expressive swirls, further enlivening the text while evoking a sense of nonpartisan freedom. “But can they divide me like the land?” Shamal asks rhetorically in Iraq. “Can they sliceme up as if I’m theirs? I ridewhere I please. Do I take sides?” Back home in the Prairies, Zephyr aptly concludes: “My home is the world.”""" ;
    ns2:title "A Boy Asked the Wind" ;
