    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Beatrice is more comfortable with numbers than people. She’s a math genius who doesn’t understand emotions and prefers applying mathematical formulas to everyday life. When she and her two best friends start their final year of high school, she devises a formula for them to become popular. It works, but not in the way they expected.\r
They each take on a persona that is carefully calculated to bring them attention. A shy math nerd, Beatrice becomes a manic pixie dream girl named Trixie: “a quirky, effervescent female who walks to the beat of her own drum and makes the male lead feel like she’s changed his world.” \r
Beatrice’s deepest friendships start to unravel as the formula starts to take effect. Through conflict, miscalculation and heartbreak, Beatrice learns to recognize and listen to her emotions and learns some important truths about human nature: “I’d found so much comfort in my precise, flawless formulas, and yet life wasn’t precise or flawless. Life was a mess. A beautiful unpredictable mess.”\r
Written in the first person, the writing reflects Beatrice’s mathematical mind, which often thinks in percentages and averages. The reader is aware of her feelings long before she is. The witty yet matter-of-fact narrative is charming, and the reader shares the discomfort of Beatrice’s friends as she denies who she truly is. The novel also features a love story that provides a behind-the-scenes tension that occasionally surfaces and takes centre stage in the final pages when Beatrice realizes that she and her best friend Spencer are in love.""" ;
    ns2:title "I'm Not Your Manic Pixie Dream Girl" ;
