    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In this truly timeless story, we first meet Ebenezer Scrooge, who “spent his days counting his money, and when each day ended, he walked home alone to an empty house, where he lived as solitary as an oyster.” \r
Scrooge hates people, hates Christmas, hates everything except accumulating wealth. But the ghosts who visit Scrooge bring teachings. The Ghost of Christmas Past shows him as a child, abandoned and alone on Christmas Day. The Ghost of Christmas Present brings him to his employee’s home, stark with poverty yet alive with the warmth of love. The Ghost of Christmas Future shares a horrifying scene depicting Scrooge’s own cold gravestone. \r
Scrooge has seen enough. “I will wipe away the shadows of what could have been,” he says and sets to work loving and helping those around him. \r
The story is true to the spirit of Dickens’ original tale, but told in a simplified manner for young readers. The illustrations are abstract watercolours, at first done in dark shades of grey to portray Scrooge’s miserable state. One page is a shadowy street scene, the buildings grey slabs with slivers of yellow light, and Scrooge’s lone figure appears in the middle. In contrast, after Scrooge’s awakening, light fills the pages. This story never gets old and is a wholesome reminder of the joy of giving and human connection—at any time of year.""" ;
    ns2:title "A Christmas Carol" ;
