ns2:Book861330f0-f33c-4afe-88ee-2223c26b4ea5 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Kate Messner" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53564" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Chronicle_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Up in the garden I stand and plan—my hands full of seeds and my head full of dreams.” When a young girl and her grandmother plan a vegetable garden, they encounter two overlapping universes: it’s spring and the ground is almost ready to be planted, while in the dirt are earthworms, slugs and centipedes working hard to prepare the soil. The story toggles back and forth between what’s happening in the dirt and what’s happening above the ground.\r
The language is poetic and beautiful: “I trail a furrow with my finger and sprinkle seeds in a careful row.… We pat them down to snuggle in the dark.”\r
The mixed-media illustrations are minimal in detail but provide busy garden scenes with all of the many plant and animal species. On one page, earthworms crawl along the bottom, tiny roots spread below the surface and tiny tender shoots reach above the ground, while wasps and honeybees hover. The colours are rich earthy tones, with dark brown soil and deep green leaves.\r
Portraying the intricate life that exists above and below the ground as well as the hard work involved in planning, planting and caring for a garden, this story will have readers eager to try out their own garden projects. Following the story is a list of species that can be found in vegetable gardens. From pill bugs to garter snakes, maintaining a garden is an elaborate team effort.""" ;
