    ns2:datePublished "1985"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Annick ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Expressive and lively language ramps up the stakes as everyone tries to get Mortimer to be quiet and go to sleep. First the mother, then the father, then “seventeen brothers and sisters,” all “thump thump thump thump thump” upstairs to tell Mortimer to be quiet. Every time, Mortimer waits until they are downstairs before loudly singing again: “Clang, clang rattle-bing-bang.”\r
Lively watercolour illustrations reflect the story’s broad humour. In one image, police officers glare over flashlights at Mortimer’s small silhouette (“MORTIMER, BE QUIET!”). In the next, Mortimer and his teddy bear peer out from under the bed. Though cowed, Mortimer still sings, inciting a fight between everyone downstairs: fingers point in all directions; a vase is upended and lampshades tilt; the mother scolds a gigantic officer of the law.\r
The final image shows Mortimer blissfully asleep in the blue shadows of his bedroom, while bright stars—strains of the fracas downstairs—float over his bed: “Mortimer got so tired of waiting for someone to come up that he fell asleep.”""" ;
