ns2:Book86712506-4805-47cc-95db-e5dd8529956d a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Lesléa Newman" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53366" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Lesléa Newman was to give a keynote speech for the University of Wyoming’s Gay Awareness Week, five days after Matthew Shepard was murdered. This is her response to the attack and its aftermath: a personal, powerful and creative compilation of 68 poems that capture the incident from a multitude of angles.\r
One poem, “Then and Now,” begins: “Then I was a sonNow I am a symbolThen I was a brotherNow I am an absence.” Another takes the point of view of a tree, imagining things it might be used for: “a serving spoon a salad bowl, a rolltop desk a rocking chair.” But the tree becomes “a small oak chest filled to the brim with ashes that were once a boy.”\r
The poems vary in form, length and point of view. Some are haiku, some are list poems, some are found poems, made of text from road signs. “Stars” is a concrete poem showing the scattered stars in the sky, which are at once witness to the crime but “unable to help being light years away.” “A Chorus of Parents” provides more of a narrative and tells of parents calling their sons after the news of Shepard’s murder.\r
Many of the poems are inspired by quotes which are provided at the top of the page: quotes from Shepard’s mother, the girlfriends of the accused and even from signs held by anti-gay protesters.\r
Newman’s unflinching poems capture a range of emotions and perspectives, from the murderers, to the fence onto which Shepard was left to die, to Shepard himself. Here you will find a sobering but beautiful tribute to a young man whose story will continue to haunt and teach readers about tolerance and awareness.""" ;
    ns2:title "October Mourning: A Song for Matthew Shepard" ;
