ns2:Book8bf2b4da-2d46-489f-a127-486abea6629c a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Cece Meng" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55723" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """When Old Turtle dies, his friends take turns remembering his life. The other turtles recall his teachings, the humpback whale his company, the otters his playfulness, the dolphins his curiosity, and the starfish his kindness. After each testimony, there is a refrain that emphasizes the depth of commemoration: “and the dolphins would always remember” … “and the starfish would always remember.” The manatee, who remembers Old Turtle snipping him free from a tangle of fishing nets, “told the story to his children, and they told the story to their children,” suggesting the legacy that intergenerational transmission weaves. The succession of eulogies for this friend who died of old age is quiet and serene. Death itself is presented somewhat euphemistically, as the ocean taking back the turtle: “on his very last day, Old Turtle swam his very last swim and took his last breath. With his life complete, the gentle waves took him away.” \r
The full-colour two-page spreads provide rich backgrounds against which the text stands out, often in white against the dark hues of the deep ocean. The marine world is textured and full of thoughtfully detailed corners and characters, and the friend whose recollections are foregrounded in turn are more brightly coloured against the shadows. Without being anthropomorphized, each animal nonetheless seems endowed with a consciousness that makes mourning plausible, from the frolicking otters to the soulful manatee. At the end, as the list of Old Turtle’s traits is summarized, a silhouetted turtle is shown rising toward the threaded brightness of the surface.""" ;
