    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "National Geographic Society"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Published by National Geographic, this large compilation book aims to make readers curious about the world by emphasizing strange, surprising and compelling facts about “stuff we knew kids would really care about.”\r
Topics are wide-ranging and intriguing. For starters, there are “15 Peanut Butter Facts That Stick,” “75 Castle Facts Fit for a King” and “35 Facts About Animals After Dark.” And so it continues, with interesting tidbits about food, holidays, the Olympics, luck, aliens and even wacky hotels.\r
Themes are laid out in a variety of visually appealing ways. For example, “35 Facts About Mummies” has fact-enclosed circles covering the two-page spread, backed by a large golden statue of a sphinx. “100 Marvelous Mammal Facts” consists of a list of numbered items, with three pictures. The inclusion of fascinating photographs, both large and small, along with regular variation in the size and colour of fonts, serves to break up the oodles of facts on each page.\r
The enticing topic titles and an extensive index make it easy and exciting for readers to find any topic that appeals to them. But take your time: fact 5,000 states that it would take the average adult “about 400 uninterrupted minutes to read this book cover to cover.”""" ;
