    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Ballet, ice cream, best friends and boys—life is sweet for devoted dancer Malie Analu. If only her parents hadn’t gotten divorced; if only Mom supported her dreams of being a professional dancer.\r
Lively language is used to construct this tale of pursuing a dream and the first flush of physical attraction, using symbols borrowed from the fairy tale classic, Cinderella. Key characters include Mom, the harried manager of the beachside ice cream shop “Once Upon a Scoop”; Lanz, the disturbingly attractive son of the new ballet teacher at the conservatory (“I noticed everything about him … I would put a stop to the dizzying effect he had on me”); and Ethan, Lanz’s friend since kindergarten who recently turned boyfriend: “He kissed me lightly, sweetly, but as he did, my mind whirred with a new, startling question. Was this lukewarm coziness how a kiss was supposed to feel?”\r
Malie’s commitment to ballet underlines the story’s messages of hard work and perseverance: “I’d broken in my pointe shoes more over the weekend, and even managed to sneak in a couple of extra hours practice … My toes and arches still ached, but I could tell they were already stronger ....” But before Malie can have her happy ending, she must learn to be honest with Mom about ballet, and honest with Lanz and Ethan about her true feelings.""" ;
