    ns2:datePublished "2008"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Stillwater is a very large panda. Koo, his young nephew, speaks in haiku and is visiting his uncle for the summer. “Tea was very goodMy cup holds emptiness nowWhere shall I put it?” he asks his uncle.\r
Stillwater has three human friends, children by the name of Addy, Michael and Karl. He takes them to see Mrs. Whitaker, a crabby elderly neighbour who has yelled at the kids in the past for playing on her lawn. But Mrs. Whitaker is ailing now and Stillwater encourages the children to help her by making soup and drawing her pictures. Soon, a friendship forms between the old woman and the children.\r
The watercolour illustrations are realistic, full of colour and life. In one, the children are making soup, while Stillwater towers in the kitchen, holding a bamboo shoot. In another, Mrs. Whitaker examines one of the drawings by lamplight. Her expression under the glow shows the softening of bitterness and what looks like the beginning of fondness. The illustrations show tenderness between Stillwater and his nephew and, eventually, between the children and Mrs. Whitaker. \r
The text is simple and mostly in the form of dialogue. In this story of interconnection, Stillwater teaches the children the pleasure of being of service to others. At the end, Karl tells Stillwater that Mrs. Whitaker was shouting at them that morning. “She was telling us to get out of the street and play in her yard.”""" ;
