ns2:Book95135f1a-e95f-408a-9523-706c65d327f0 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "David McKee" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53229" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2004"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Anderson_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In the storybook language of a fable, this tale contrasts themes of war, oppression and conformity, with peaceful accommodation and interpenetration of cultures. The General’s nation invades and occupies neighbouring countries: “They had a very strong army, and they had the cannon. . . . ‘It’s for their own good,’ he said. ‘So they can be like us.’”\r
Sweet, simple drawings in pen and coloured pencil effects create diagram-like compositions to represent the sophisticated concepts in the story. In one image, a troop of rosy-cheeked soldiers marches in perfect formation for the General’s parade. Observant readers will note that despite their uniformity, each man’s profile is individuated. Images depicting the response of the invaded country show scattershot compositions of cozy houses, a wishing well and friendly gatherings with food and music. In this war, the army is not resisted, but rather absorbed by warm welcome.\r
At loose ends, the invaders help with chores, enjoy the local cuisine and put aside their uniforms in favour of local clothing. There is the opportunity to examine diversity in our own society, when the powerful nation is reverse-infiltrated by customs of the little country. The General believes these are “The spoils of war.” Readers may think otherwise.""" ;
    ns2:title "Conquerors" ;
