    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54396" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Toon_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In this brief and stylish non-fiction picture book, expressive yet simple language conveys key information about earthworms. “‘My tunnels bring air and water to the soil to help plants grow.’ When worms dig, twisting and turning, they make the earth … earthier.”\r
Artful illustrations use sketchy lines and subtle painterly effects to create cutaway scenes of worm tunnels—children experience a variety of reactions ( “Worms are cool!” “Maybe to you!”)—and one very interested bird: Hello little worm! ... I said HELLO little worm!”\r
One scene shows a worm underground, eating and evacuating (“My poop is good for soil”) while, above ground, a child grimaces: “EEW!” A double-page spread offers a simple yet remarkable diagram on earthworm anatomy. (“OUTSIDE: worms don’t have lungs. They breathe through their skin … INSIDE: … 5 pairs of hearts..”)\r
As a skillful editorial unveils the facts, understanding and knowledge engender appreciation among the child characters. They pursue their subject with cameras and microphones: “How big is the biggest worm in the world?” Meanwhile the bird’s opinion remains unchanged (“‘want to have lunch with me?”); so the worm tunnels away: “Sorry, Bluebird. I have important work to do.”""" ;
    ns2:title "We Dig Worms!" ;
