ns2:Book96409f86-79a9-4b19-883c-32b1ecc7316d a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Andrea Mills" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54198" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "DK"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Divided into six sections, this collection of short biographies introduces readers to important women throughout history in the fields of art, science, activism, politics, entrepreneurship and overall achievement. These historical figures range from Sappho, in the seventh century BCE, to contemporary inspirations like Serena Williams and Malala Yousafzai. Within each category, subgroups offer a closer thematic focus, gathering shorter biographical notes. In “Inspiring Campaigners,” for instance, the “Landmark Moments” highlights the contributions of Rachel Carson, Helen Keller, Wangari Maathai (“the first African woman to receive the Nobel Peace Prize”) and others. The language of the brief introduction to each section is simple and engaging— “girl power is in action around the world,” the preface to “Leading Ladies” reads—and the write-ups themselves provide historical context as they illustrate the impact of each woman.\r
The book is brightly and lavishly illustrated with pictures, drawings and reproductions of documents. Each woman is represented in caricature style, with a large photograph or painting of her head poised over a smaller body, and each is surrounded by pictures of objects related to her work or cause—a sword for Joan of Arc, a microphone for Eleanor Roosevelt, a painting frame for Peggy Guggenheim. The information is presented in different font sizes and occasionally in bold. Some sections are enclosed in speech bubbles and other shapes (details including how Junko Tabei, the first woman to climb Mount Everest, changed the world are lined up inside a hiking boot).\r
A list of other amazing women makes up an appendix titled “Let’s Applaud”; the book also includes a glossary and an index.""" ;
