    ns2:datePublished "1985"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """With economical and poignant language, this gripping story brings South Africa’s apartheid to life through the voyage of two brave siblings, Naledi and Tiro, aged just 13 and 9. Penniless, they must make the trek from their small village to Johannesburg to inform their mother of their sister’s acute illness.\r
The journey is recounted in an intimate third-person voice, with empathy and vivid descriptions that show how both siblings, but especially Naledi, are learning and experiencing new things and questioning everything around them. The racist conditions and history of apartheid are skilfully woven into the high-stakes tale, such as being checked at a train station for the pass that every black citizen over 16 had to carry.\r
On their journey the siblings start to question and make sense of their highly corrupt and oppressive society. “Freedom. What did the word really mean?” wonders Naledi. The tale necessarily contains harsh realities like the death of a baby at the hospital and the memory of their father who died from an illness related to his work in a mine: “these mountains of sand had taken their father forever.”\r
Luckily, there is comradeship among the miseries and hope at the end of the story: it seems their sister will live and Naledi is becoming politically active.\r
Extra material can be used to further delve into the subject, including a letter from the author about why she wrote the book, which was once banned, and a concise history of apartheid.""" ;
