ns2:Book988517f4-af3c-4957-bc09-c1c58e70a223 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "David Milgrim" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54567" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:MacMilan ;
    ns2:reviewBody """We all have feelings: some pleasant, others purely painful. This playful book focuses on the latter, addressing a touchy topic with sensitivity.\r
“Do you sometimes feel as sad as a lost kitten in the rain?” asks the narrator. “Or as small as a mouse?” Each page illustrates a child disguised as an animal that embodies the feeling experienced. The implication is that feelings are as impermanent as costumes—and not necessarily reflective of who you are overall. You might wear that feeling for a while, but not forever.\r
An illustration of a child dressed as a lion, shouting at a woman’s ankles, is paired with the lines, “Do you sometimes get really, really, rrrrrrreally mad?” The next spread amplifies this feeling, showing the same child kicking things, still in temper-tantrum-lion-mode, while the text reads: “And feel totally out of control, and you don’t even know why?” The words “out of control” bulge from the page in a larger font size to emphasize the child’s distress.\r
Refreshingly, no attempts are made to resolve this negativity. The narrator doesn’t offer advice on how to cope with bad feelings or how to get rid of them faster. On the contrary, a non-judgmental ending prompts readers to release any shame around such experiences. “It’s only natural,” says the narrator, his words humorously paired with a picture of a naked kid, free of all disguises, running free as a bird among the flowers.""" ;
    ns2:title "Wild Feelings" ;
