    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In this almost wordless adventure story, the only text appears as newspaper headlines at the beginning and end of the book. Fifty years ago, two children claimed to have seen a giant spotted whale, but no one bought their story. Now, fifty years later, the grandchildren of the whale spotters set out in search of the spotted whale. Not only do they find the whale, they manage to capture images, which appear in the headlines at the end of the book.\r
The illustrations are done in pencil and are exceptionally detailed. Through hatching and shading, the illustrations capture complex facial expressions and stormy seas. On one page, after the children’s boat capsizes, water is dripping from their clothes. The boy’s expression is that of discomfort and defeat while the girl’s shows disbelief. Sometimes the sketches are smaller studies linked together to tell a story. On one page, four small sketches show an ear, an eye, a whale breathing at the surface, and the two children running to the lookout platform.\r
In this riveting adventure, generous illustrations invite the reader to linger in the scenes, taking in the action and soaking in the details. The final headlines include a quote from the original whale spotters: “All these years no one believed our story, and now our very own flesh and blood have proved us right. We’ll be celebrating in style tonight!”""" ;
