ns2:Book9a75cc75-638c-4cdd-857a-cddb06fdb6a8 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Charlotte Milner" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56109" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Penguin Random HouseDK Children's"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This non-fiction picture book about bats celebrates the ecological contributions of a much-maligned mammal. Twenty-two short two-page sections introduce young readers to bat anatomy, habitat, behaviour, nutrition and adaptations, and it exhaustively explains why “bats play an important role in keeping the natural world healthy.” Almost every biotope, from the savanna to the rainforest, benefits from the presence of bats, which contribute to reseeding and distribution, plant biodiversity and pollination. Frequent connections are made to humans’ role in the depletion of bat populations, but also to the myriad ways humans depend on bats, notably because of their role as pollinators. The book also touches on common myths and fears about bats (vampirism, contagion, superstition). Finally, several sections address threats to global bat populations, including habitat loss, pesticide use, noise pollution and hunting, and offer accessible solutions young readers can apply to help maintain or restore bat populations… and therefore make the whole planet healthier. An index of species concludes the book. \r
\r
The detailed colour illustrations are both representative and realistic—with different species clearly distinguished, for instance—and sufficiently playful to be compelling to young readers, as when fruit bats nibble quaintly on wild figs. Created by layering digital renderings of hand paintings, the images of the bats have texture and depth. The scenes featuring bats are accompanied by graphics depicting various aspects of bat zoology and of their ecological contributions: an inset shows a seedling that sprouted from bat droppings, which contain seeds, for example; a footer illustrates the various foods that bats make possible; and a row of circles and arrows points out features of bat anatomy.""" ;
