ns2:Book9eaafc95-0b87-46c9-bf28-8517f343fa92 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Daniel Miyares" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54427" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Expressive language and artful images convey this tale that features polite expressions, a cranky little bird and a surprise ending. “Pardon me” is this story’s amusing refrain, as a little bird’s island perch in the swamp becomes increasingly crowded by a passing crane, a leaping frog and a paddling turtle.\r
Lush illustrations use delicate line and texture with vivid colour to portray the animal characters in minimal settings. White clouds spread like ink in water, among deep blue skies. Confident brush strokes convey the emotional currents beneath the polite language. One spread is dominated by the squatting crane, whose beaky smile welcomes a sleepy-eyed frog onto the last patch of space, while the besieged little bird squints from under the crane’s fluffy wing: “It’s crowded already, don’t you think?”\r
“Pardon me, but you’re sitting on a . . .” When a passing fox’s friendly greeting is interrupted by the exasperated bird, notions of patience and tolerance seem to scatter, just as the animals do: “Well, PARDON ME, but this is my perch and I don’t care what you have to say!” Alone a last, the bird enjoys peace for a single, rosy sunset spread, before his perch reveals itself to be a submerged alligator. Final images show the alligator (“Burp!”) with a long, toothy smirk: “Pardon me.” The endpaper shows a lone yellow feather floating on the water.""" ;
