ns2:Booka3ade350-6720-4711-aed1-7332967d21d2 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Kadir Nelson" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54601" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The text is short and simple but the message unmistakably universal: “reap what you sow.” A tale about a rabbit and a mouse bring this proverb to life. In the first pages, they plant tomato, carrot and cabbage seeds and “in time, with love and care,” they get tomato, carrot and cabbage plants. “If you plant a seed of selfishness,” the text continues, “in a very short time, it will grow and grow and grow into a heap of trouble.”\r
\r
The narrative is told largely through the illustrations, which have elements of realism as well as cartoon. Done in rich oil paints, they feature animals, namely a rabbit and a mouse, who are learning these lessons firsthand. The rabbit and mouse are lifelike, with large expressive eyes and anthropomorphic body language as they plant seeds and leap for joy when their plants grow. The lifelike birds feature a crow, a blue jay, a cardinal and a dove.\r
\r
When the birds show interest in their harvest, rabbit and mouse respond with aggression, which leads to a chaotic food fight. “But if you plant a seed of kindness,” the text continues, “in almost no time at all the fruits of kindness will grow and grow and grow.” The illustrations show the birds planting seeds from the sky and the final page shows many different animals feasting together on their collective harvest.""" ;
    ns2:title "If You Plant a Seed" ;
