    ns2:datePublished "2010"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Large type and lots of photos give youngsters access to an early South American civilization, the Inca. Chapters such as “City in the Mountains” and “Rise to Power” introduce the land, food and lifestyle in short sections, under clear headings. The section “Staying Connected” discusses the vast mileage of roads and bridges built “across jungles, rivers, mountains and deserts.” Captions in various type sizes will attract young readers: “The Inca army carried drums, flutes, and trumpets into battle.”\r
Photographs bring the lasting accomplishments of the Inca to children, while showing them a fascinating region in our contemporary world. Reproductions of historic art include battles and portraits of Inca rulers. Young readers’ reactions to the photo of an Inca mummy will likely be strong—possibly stronger still when they learn of its spiritual importance to the Inca, and how most Inca mummies were destroyed by Spanish Conquistadors. The book ends with an emphasis on Inca traits that continue in the language and culture of the Quechua people today.\r
Back material includes statistics, further resources, a glossary and an index, as well as the answer key to two true-false questions posed at the beginning of the book.""" ;
    ns2:title "Inca Empire" ;
