    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Chronicle_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Creating images and meaning with language is the focus of this comic-book-like story, as the Gumshoe Zoo animal detectives solve the mystery of who smashed Mr. Hound’s grocery store window. Animal-related idioms flow with abundance, as the team tries different ways to express themselves. Quentin the goat (“There’s something fishy going on here”) apologizes to Reggie the fish (“definite monkey business at hand, my friend”), who apologizes to Steve the monkey (“I agree, I smell a rat”), who apologizes to Josie the rat, and so on. \r
Graphic style illustrations use strong lines, simple forms and flat colour fills to depict the animals at the crime scene, brandishing notepads, tweezers and magnifying glasses, as they piece together the clues to solve the mystery— they eventually find their answer in the misspelled sign painted on the smashed window: “‘You didn’t want to pay an arm and a leg to fix it.’… ‘What’s the matter? Cat got your tongue?’ ‘Hold your horses! I won’t be your scapegoat!’” \r
Readers may be inspired to discuss possible origins for the expressions in this story, suggest others, or invent some of their own. A final spread uses a fun bulletin board layout to define and discuss a variety of idioms and their meanings.""" ;
    ns2:title "Fowl Play" ;
