    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Second_Story_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Ever heard of the Black Cross nurses? How about the transgendered 1960s pop singer Jackie Shane? Or Rosa Pryor and her famed Vancouver restaurant, Chicken Inn? This valuable book highlights little-known Black historic figures and activist groups, many with a Canadian connection, through brief biographies and original artwork.\r
Featured are fascinating individuals such as centenarian Sylvia Estes Stark, (1839-1944) who, in response to the US Fugitive Slave Act, immigrated to Salt Spring Island, BC, where she “developed many skills, from fending off wild animals to learning the Chinook Wawa trade language.” Activist clubs and organizations are also profiled, such as the Coloured Women’s Club (“founded over a century ago in 1902 in Montreal, Quebec”) and The Hour-A-Day Study Club founded in Windsor, ON in 1935: “Today, the club is still active and provides scholarships for Black students.’”\r
Richly-imagined artwork embeds realistic portraiture within symbolic compositions. For example, Mary Miles Bibb (1820-1877) is shown writing by candlelight, which seems to cast an atmospheric background image depicting travelers on the Underground Railroad.\r
From the story of Chloe Cooley—enslaved in Upper Canada in 1793—to today’s founders of Blocko “all-day celebration of Blackness of all genders and sexualities,” this book offers a sense of pride, along with knowledge and awareness of Black Canadian women’s history.""" ;
