    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This celebration of the self and all its possibilities is told through rhythmic, rhyming text that is catchy and fun: “No matter your volume, your age or your size,YOU have the power to be a surprise.” The text acknowledges the different ways of being, free of judgment or expectations: “Maybe you’re funny.Or bookish.Or fast.Or maybe you’re always decidedly last.” The mixed media illustrations offer a pastel palette, a variety of textures and some humorous details. One girl who “likes counting” stands on a chair, making pencil marks on the wall while her dog sneakily gobbles spilled cereal on the floor. Below her, a young girl licks her lips in concentration as she sits on the floor, drawing. The wall behind her is adorned with her art. The children are as diverse as the activities, ensuring an inclusive vibe throughout.\r
The text not only encourages the reader to celebrate who they are but suggests how they can help: “Don’t sit on the sidelines.Be part of the fray.Go after your passions a little each day.” The accompanying illustration shows a team of children with recycling bags, picking up plastic along the side of a river. The opposite page shows children working together to mend a wagon wheel: “Find what needs fixing.Repair what you can.Then choose a new problem and do it again.” The empowering message to accept oneself also transfers to others in a celebration of diversity, strength and the passion of each individual.""" ;
