ns2:Bookab9a686f-f94d-4600-8241-ddd694014394 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Chris Naylor-Ballesteros" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56110" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Allen & Unwin"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book tells a sweet story about moving, home and new friends. A strange green creature shows up one day, looking weary and toting a big suitcase. When the gathered animals—a fox, a rabbit and a chicken—ask about the suitcase’s contents, the newcomer explains that it contains a teacup, and a table and chair, and indeed a whole house. Home, the wistful newcomer explains, is “on a hillside surrounded by trees and on a clear day you can see the sea. It’s all there, in my suitcase.” The others are skeptical, and when the green newcomer falls asleep, they break open the suitcase to see for themselves. Sure enough, inside the suitcase there is a teacup—now broken—and a worn sepia photograph of the newcomer having tea at a table in front of a little cabin. The other animals are contrite, “What will he think of us?” and when the newcomer wakes up, he finds that they have built him a new house and glued the teacup back together. The only problem now, he says, is that “we’re going to need more teacups.” \r
The suitcase stands as a metaphor for what we take with us, what we carry. The story’s simple consideration of the complexities of encountering a stranger, and of the emotional response to any sort of migration, is told in sparing text and straightforward language that teaches the importance of empathy and retribution, and raises nuanced questions about the nature of home. \r
\r
The accompanying ink and watercolour images both echo the simplicity of the text and add a deeper dimension by depicting what the stranger has left behind. When the green newcomer talks or dreams about the home he left behind, the paintings are rendered in the muted browns of memory, while the present moment is vibrant—the fox, rabbit and chicken are brightly painted in warm orange, yellow and red, and new home for the stranger -who’s-not-a-stranger-anymore is built of multicoloured boards. The characters are silly but clearly and plausibly expressive, and their respective dialogue is printed in the colour of each one.""" ;
