    ns2:reviewBody "Maple’s parents planted a maple tree in her honour before she was even born. Maple and her tree have a special bond. She sings and sways for her tree. And the tree does things for her too: “On some days, when the wind was just right, Maple would simply lie under the tree, and its leaves would dance just for her.” When Maple becomes a big sister, she tries her best to help the baby. “If the baby was cold, Maple gave the baby her hat and gloves. If the baby was lonely, Maple would share her special friends.” But when the baby was really upset, Maple would take her outside to her tree and the tree would dance for them both. The illustrations are simple and sparsely done in pencil and with digitally rendered colour. They focus on Maple and the tree, with little to no background. The colour use is minimal, except for Maple’s clothes and the rich greens and reds of her tree’s leaves. Most pages feature small images of Maple but one two-page spread features Maple lying on her back with lush green leaves that seem to dance in the sunlight. The text is simple but nuanced, with elements of humour: “Sometimes when Maple was noisy (which was a lot), her parents sent her outside to play.” Maple is a story of a child's bond with nature. It is a reminder of the simple beauty of a tree, the stillness that nature provides and the importance for children to experience this unique relationship." ;
