    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """After a bumpy first period of hockey, the Zamboni machine only has 18 minutes to make sure the ice is smooth for the players—but “can he fix ice THIS bad?” the commentator asks. The book is written as a dialogue between the commentator and the Zamboni, the former shouting jeers and encouragement, the latter methodically inventorying the “dents and pits and ruts.” When the “talker dude” puts the pressure on—“Shazamboni!”—our mechanical friend shifts into high ice-shaving gear. The book mentions some of the technical particularities of the Zamboni, such as the level auger that “spins snow to center” and playfully and onomatopoeically outlines the usually overlooked ice maintenance that takes place between periods.\r
Full-page colour illustrations show various scenes from a hockey game—with players first tripping and tumbling on the rutted ice, then zooming over the newly cleaned surface. The Zamboni is a bright orange and purple machine, cutely anthropomorphized: the hood is its mouth; its eyes are where a windshield would be, shining beams onto the frozen imperfections. The commentator is often shown in a page corner, his heckling pouring over the page in loosely drawn speech bubbles, while the Zamboni’s responses weave over the page, following the tracks and whirls above the rink.\r
It won’t be just hockey-lovers who fall for this “blade-packing, ice-shaving, snow-eating, water-spraying, slush-slurping, towel-dragging, triple-tank truck.”""" ;
