    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Tom loves the winter. He doesn’t mind that it has lasted longer than ever before and that there is no sign of spring. But Tom’s mother is worried about Nana. “It’s been too cold, too long, for an old woman,” she says to Tom. “Nana needs the spring sun.” But winter is relentless because Winter’s Child, a boy that Tom meets in the forest, does not want to go to sleep. The two play together every day until there is no more firewood left. Nana’s health is waning and Winter’s Child understands he must take his leave.
The illustrations are a striking blend of traditional media and digital techniques, which results in organic textures, such as tree bark, as well as otherworldly effects like the snowflake designs that shimmer in the wind and in the smoke rising from the chimney. The extremely detailed illustrations are rich with the magic of winter. On one page the northern lights ripple in the night sky. In another, icicles sparkle and the boys’ snow sculptures come to life. 
The language is simple yet contains the poetry of a fable: “I strayed from my father because I wasn’t ready to sleep,” says Winter’s Child to Tom. “I wanted the winter to last forever, but I have played too long.” 
While most of the book is illustrated in white and shades of blue, the final page is a radiant spring scene full of colour and life, with new leaves and blossoms, streams, fish and birds.""" ;
