    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic_Canada ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This hilarious tale lampoons sibling relations and babysitting solutions, as Danielle—the eldest in a family of five children—is ordered by her stressed mother to take care of the other kids during the frantic last-minute rush of a family move.\r
Dramatic language sets the stage for general uproar: “Her dad was yelling, ‘The moving truck is coming, the moving truck is coming!’ Her mom was yelling, ‘In boxes, in boxes! Everything in boxes!’”\r
Expressive illustrations in sketchy pencil line and watercolour fills are rife with humour and detail. One image shows the mother bent under an overflowing box, surrounded by household detritus such as Christmas ornaments, firecrackers and broken dishes. (“Danielle, don’t just stand there. Do something. Pack something. Take care of the little kids. Take care of your little sister.”) The next image shows sister Julianne’s half-packed room, complete with a giant, open box, specially decorated with childish drawings. Danielle’s smile is beatific as she plunks her bemused sibling into the box.\r
This book’s tongue-in-cheek jibe at the hallowed tradition of top-down sibling-care (and clueless parents) is made sublime and ridiculous, as three more individuated siblings are packed away by Danielle—and moved across town in the truck. The riotous cycle is complete when, unpacked in their new home, the younger ones get together and chase Danielle with a big empty box: the final image shows nothing but a thoroughly taped box—with eyes bugging out the peephole.""" ;
