ns2:Bookb67a3415-5242-4ef8-8134-01737c8fcaa6 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Norah McClintock" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53225" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Orca ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Everybody bikes the wrong way up that one-way street on the way to school. Then, for just a moment, Kenzie glances away from the road. Before he knows it, his bicycle is on top of him, while beneath him on the pavement, in a pool of blood, lies Stassi, his ex-girlfriend. Details of Kenzie’s habitually careless biking come to light, as does the truth about his complicated recent breakup with Stassi. After the accident, the police focus on the rules of the road at first, but soon the prospect of a fine turns into an assault charge. Stassi may have brain damage, and it seems someone has come forward claiming Kenzie hit her deliberately. \r
This short novel, written in highly accessible prose, provides a cautionary tale. The present tense gives the narrative a compelling immediacy. The first-person point of view includes a teenager’s sharp observations of the adult world, notably the way Kenzie’s father condescends to his mother. The tone is plausible and wry, even under emotional duress. When his mom kindly makes him his favourite breakfast, for instance, Kenzie finds that his appetite, “which I thought was missing in action, suddenly reports for duty.”\r
One Way is an engaging crash novel, with a likeable protagonist and a lesson learned.""" ;
