ns2:Bookbfc8ffb9-d522-4e1b-ba5f-f63d71eb74b7 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Ibtihaj with S.K. Ali Muhammad" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54738" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Little, Brown and Company"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This charming story about wearing one’s differences with pride is told from the perspective of a little girl, Faizah, whose big sister Asiya is starting grade six and wearing her new hijab for the very first time: “Mama holds out the pink. Mama loves pink.” \r
A skilful, low-key plot begins with notions of women’s choices and multigenerational expressions of faith, as Mama and the sisters shop for Asiya’s scarf: “…behind the counter is the brightest blue.” \r
Poetic language highlights evocative details of the first day of school: “A new backpack, new light-up shoes,” while conveying underlying emotions: “I’m walking with a princess. So I pretend I’m one too…” and, “My first-day hijab is going to be blue too.” \r
Sweet illustrations of wide-eyed schoolchildren depict variety in fashion, hairstyle, body shape and ethnicity, with subtle textures and expressive markings in crayon- and watercolour effects. Compositions depict both real-life settings and symbolic imaginings. One spread shows Faizah queuing with other kindergarteners against an atmospheric backdrop of speckled brick wall, “‘What’s that on your sister’s head?’… ‘A scarf,’ I whisper back. I don’t know why a whisper came out.” Another shows her turning cartwheels across the schoolyard to spy on taunting sixth graders, represented as dotted shadow-silhouettes, “I’m going to pull that tablecloth off your head!” \r
The book’s message of managing one’s differences with pride and poise is reflected in images showing Asiya and her friends playing tag on a rolling blue ground that is her headscarf, as well as a spare and striking composition depicting Faizah’s own footsteps, as she dashes from the huffing shadow-bully. In the end, self-determination overpowers fears, and little Faizah is relieved to find her sister waiting for her after school: “Like it’s a regular day. She’s smiling. Strong. Because Asiya’s hijab is like the ocean and the sky, no line between them… like sisters. Like me and Asiya.” \r
An author’s note discusses the real-life inspiration for this story, with photos of the Olympic athlete author and her two sisters, Faizah and Asiya (wearing a hijab).""" ;
    ns2:title "Proudest Blue: A Story of Hijab and Family" ;
