    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Conundrum Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody "In May 2009, Alison McCreesh bought a used minivan and drove to Yellowknife. Always sketching in her comic book diary, she started uploading her drawings, sometimes made on coffee-stained paper, onto a blog. Now these comics, rendered in pen and watercolour, are collected in Ramshackle. What’s it like to move to a new place? To live in the north? This graphic novel follows McCreesh’s first summer in Yellowknife. Life isn’t always rosy. McCreesh and her boyfriend sleep in the van in an abandoned parking lot. They fight off mosquitos. They have no toilet. They can’t find others who appreciate music and alternative culture like they do. That is, until they volunteer at a local festival and meet friends who live in the woodyard, a community of counterculture shack dwellers. Together, they smoke, drink and share their discoveries of Yellowknife. McCreesh’s drawings are expressive and fluid. Black and white or coloured in muted tones, they’re overlaid with speech and narration bubbles that guide the reader through the story. Colourful full-page splash pages, panel strips and collages show us McCreesh’s Yellowknife: her fun and sad times there, the city’s landscapes and people. Interesting facts are presented in out-of-story layouts on topics like the history of the city, what causes the solstice, and how to use a homemade porta-potty. McCreesh is a keen observer, her remarks are funny and moving. Readers feel her thrill, and her loneliness. Readers will find visual clues about the way characters feel: drawings of McCreesh have no mouth when she’s in a boring office job; speech bubbles of background chatter overlap and fall off the page, illegible.. Ramshackle is a memoir about starting a new life, but it is ultimately about what it means to be a citizen; what it means to become part of—and help create—a community." ;
    ns2:title "Ramshackle: A Yellowknife Story" ;
