    ns2:datePublished "2003"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Set around gritty northwest Toronto and a catacomb-like lost-and-found department, this mystery-thriller delivers suspense and engaging characters through tight, witty writing. Vinny’s shame over his deformed arm, a depressed co-worker, a blistering heat wave and an increasingly filthy fast-food uniform help create an atmosphere of unease. Duncan’s own haunted memories of a drowning girl drive him forward.\r
Balancing all this darkness are Duncan’s supportive parents, his feelings for his ex-girlfriend and the tough-yet-tender friendship between the boys. “Anybody can swim. Before we were apes, we were fish. I don’t tell Vinny about the fish thing because his nickname in school—what the idiots call him—is Flipper. Because of his left arm.” \r
Adventures include tracking the predator (“… he goes right on Cedar Road… I sprint across and almost get pancaked by a truck”), breaking and entering (“This must be the door to his cage, the one he broke through years ago”) and a harrowing chase scene (“at the top of the stairs I sense him right behind me. I explode into the hallway…”) In the end, this gripping tale deftly portrays a message of self-empowerment and its potential to heal the past.""" ;
