ns2:Bookc21616eb-d3f8-4d81-b86f-9fe1cd2458ec a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Julie Morstad" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52824" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Simply_Read_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In this sweet, simple and gorgeously illustrated book, young readers are encouraged to consider everyday activities in a new light.\r
Language mingles the mundane with the poetic, in brief phrases for each spread: “how to watch where you’re going,” “how to stay close,” “how to disappear.”\r
The illustrations combine powerful composition with delicate images and fine detailing. “How to see the wind” depicts children in a field of waving grasses. High above, in a blank white sky, kites and balloons fly. Closing in, readers will see the frame behind the butterfly kite, the ribbing in a little boy’s sweater and individual strands in the girls’ flowing hair. In another spread, friends pile up between layers of stacked pillows. Colour and pattern combinations manage to be both muted and riotous, for a stunning effect: “how to make a sandwich.”\r
A child lies along a tree branch, peeking from a spatter of russet leaves: “how to be faraway.” Another child lingers at the top of a steep slide, the empty space around her providing a potent image of risk and the unknown: “how to be brave.” Artistically, poetically and thematically, this is an excellent book for readers of any age.""" ;
