    ns2:publisher ns2:MacMilan ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Finding one’s true nature is the uplifting message in this tale of a little crocodile who can’t swim. Delicately textured images use meandering line work, smudges and watercolour to gorgeous effect. Homey scenes include the croc family in the bath, on the diving board and in the river. In one image, the little crocodile’s eyes roll with concern as he dips a toe in the water. Another shows him perched on a tree branch, alone with his floaty-ring, as the others frolic in the river below.\r
Expressive language and type layout convey the crocodile’s internal conflicts: “And although climbing the ladder was fun, he just didn’t want to J U M P.” His final attempt to join the swimmers combines drama with charm: “One, twooo, two and a half THREEEEE! S P L O S H GLUG HELP!”\r
When a fiery sneeze reveals his identity as a dragon, true strengths emerge as fast as his sprouting wings. This pervasive message is underlined in the final image, showing a clutch of dragon’s eggs, with one crocodile egg among them. Broad tail curled around them all, the expectant mother-dragon reads a book: “The Dragon Who Didn’t Like Fire.”""" ;
