    ns2:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Orca ;
    ns2:reviewBody "Through four somewhat dense chapters, “The Kid Next Door,” Partying in the Streets,” “A Potluck of Possibilities” and “Life in the City,” this uplifting non-fiction picture book examines practical ways neighbours around the world are making their city streets friendlier places to be. “Charles Darwin (1809-1882), who studied evolution, believed in survival of the fittest and also survival of the kindest. In other words, he said creatures that work well together are the most likely to survive.” Clear, conversational language offers a historic look at humankind’s living environments—from our nomadic ancestors, through agriculture, industrialization and the birth of big cities and car-culture—before showcasing inspiring examples of community-building around the world. Ideas include temporary transformations (such as summertime sand for a riverside expressway), permanent installations (such as the closing of New York City’s Times Square to car-traffic) and activism to create better, safer spaces within communities: “But one group of grandmothers refused to hide away indoors. Instead, the women dragged lawn chairs to the most crime-ridden corners and started knitting. The result? The drug dealers took off and never came back.” An abundance of captioned, quality photography depicts people enjoying the fruits of these ideas, be it a skate park near Perth, Australia, a brightly painted intersection (“Share-It Square”) in Portland, OR, community ovens in a Moroccan village and in Toronto, ON, and much more. One photo depicts an ingenious mural of children playing under a sky filled with flowers: “Sometimes you can decorate by taking something away—like the dirt on this wall… it’s reverse (or clean) graffiti.” Sidebars include anecdotes from the author’s own life, emphasizing the book’s message that it can take as little as one person, or a family, to effect change. Back material includes a glossary and an index." ;
    ns2:title "Home Sweet Neighborhood: Transforming Cities One Block at a Time" ;
