    ns2:datePublished "1997"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Little_Brown ;
    ns2:reviewBody """“Cereal boxes at the breakfast table … seed catalogues … the inscription on the monument in the town square, and books.” Some children may recognize Edward’s passion for reading; others might be surprised.\r
Through books, Edward’s world is replete with adventure: Robin Hood, Joan of Arc, dinosaurs and more. When he finds a strange book tucked on the library shelf, he accidentally brings a band of pirates to life.\r
Painted illustrations are imbued with shadowy atmosphere. Sea water pours over Edward’s bed as the pirates arrive. One scene shows them offering him a share of treasure, the lantern’s glow reflecting on a chest full of gold. In the next, he and his teddy bear teeter on the edge of the pirate plank, as a shark circles the waters below.\r
The thrill of imagination, and its power, are shown when Edward tames his scary fantasy by introducing his mom (entering on a horse, like Joan of Arc) and his dad, (looking rather like Robin Hood, shooting arrows into the bedroom). In the end, with permission from Joan-Mom and Robin-Dad, Edward stays up late, reading to the pirates, who—it turns out—can’t read.""" ;
