    ns2:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Scholastic_Canada ;
    ns2:reviewBody """The Sugar Bush is a simple but comprehensive guide to maple syrup production, including the tapping of the trees, the weather conditions needed for a maple tree to produce sap and the extensive boiling process. It includes practical references to help the reader relate to the figures provided: “A sugar maple produces about 50 litres of sap each year. That’s the same as 25 large cartons of milk.” \r
\r
The photos that accompany the text illustrate the concepts being described. A close-up of the hand brace drilling into the tree shows how the holes are made. The next page features the spile coming out of the tree with sap dripping out. The text reads: “Have you ever thought about how it would be if you could attach a spile to your nose when you have a cold?” \r
\r
The book explains the temperature at which the sap must be boiled to become syrup, taffy and maple sugar. Reference is made to Indigenous peoples, who would dip a wooden spatula with a hole in it into the syrup and blow. If a bubble formed the syrup was ready. The book finishes with a picture of a typical menu at the sugar bush: pancakes, baked beans, pea soup, eggs, ham and pork rinds, a meal that is “inspired by the era of lumberjack camps where men lived during the long winter months as they logged trees.”""" ;
