    ns2:publisher ns2:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This wordless picture book follows a boy and his beloved boat made of newspaper. The opening page features two sets of hands, one small and one big, folding newspaper. The following page shows the boy at the top of the front steps holding his boat. His yellow boots, raincoat and hat are vibrant against the grey and black shading of the house and sky. \r
\r
The watercolour illustrations, drawn using digital tools, are a blend of abstract and realism. They are mostly without colour except for the faint red and blue squares on the newspaper and the boy’s yellow rain gear, which provide stark contrast. One two-page spread shows a yellow blob obscured by countless white and grey streaks of rain. Another shows the boy launching his boat into a puddle with houses in the background, reflected clearly in the water, like a photograph.\r
\r
When the boy’s boat is swept away by fast-moving flood water, he chases after it, his face full of desperation. The boat slips into a storm drain and the boy eventually finds it destroyed in the stream below. He returns home deflated, but his dad knows what to do: he dries him off, makes hot chocolate and gets out more newspaper. This time they make a plane. When the boy opens the door again, the sky is now yellow and his clothes are grey. The final pages show him running, holding his paper plane up to a butter-yellow sky.""" ;
