ns2:Bookce1ed3af-3739-46ce-8c7e-8ed59938cb3b a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Meghan McCarthy" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56314" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """In 1987, what was supposed to be a week-long trip down the eastern seaboard of the USA turned into a five-month voyage stuck at sea for the garbage barge engaged to ship over 3000 tons of New York trash to South Carolina, with plans to turn it into methane, then electrical energy. Turned away from port, the barge travels to Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana, the Florida Keys—and is even chased out of Mexican waters by the Mexican navy. Followed by news media, rejected by local residents at each port of call, the barge is eventually allowed to return its load back home, where it is burned into 400 tons of ash. \r
\r
“Finally the barge was spotted floating in circles in the Gulf of Mexico. The mayor of Grand Isle in Louisiana said, probably with some relief, ‘Wherever this stuff goes, it’s going to be somebody else’s problem.’ And it was.” \r
\r
Clear and engaging language recounts this amusing yet unnerving true story, highlighting our desperate need for better waste-management solutions: “Then more experts arrived. There was the toxicologist, environmental specialist, solid waste specialist and vermin specialist. For several days, they picked through the trash.” Hand-painted illustrations use cheerful colours to depict both the trash and beautiful images of seascapes and ocean life. “Florida citizens wanted nothing to do with all that trash.” \r
\r
Humorous, stylized renderings of the real-life players include barge captain, Duffy St. Pierre, (“We’d like to go ashore. We’re only human”), politicians (“I think he needs to chug along. We’re the jewel of Florida”), TV news anchors (“The barge has quickly become a symbol of the country’s growing problems with trash”), and more. \r
\r
Throughout the story, there are many opportunities for discussion about the environment, and solutions for minimizing our impact on it. Of course, this tale can offer no single, happy solution to a problem that remains with us, but it can encourage further research into progress made since those days—in our recycling habits as well as scientific processes for garbage transformation. Back material offers further information on the journey, with photos, as well as facts about recycling and ocean garbage.""" ;
    ns2:title "All That Trash: The Story of the 1987 Garbage Barge and Our Problem with Stuff" ;
