ns2:Bookd08253e9-b3b8-4806-acad-dcb7953bcc26 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Elaine Moser" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54007" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Taylor witnesses her older sister’s autopsy after she is murdered by her abusive boyfriend. Left to care for her 6-year-old nephew, Mason, she moves to her Gram’s house and starts a new life. But Taylor’s abusive and controlling boyfriend, Devon, will not let her go. She makes a new friend in tall, feisty Lily, finding new strength in the friendship, until Devon turns up, kidnapping Lily and Taylor and forcing them to fight for their lives.\r
The story is told through the ordinary details of youth, contrasted with the horrors of violence. The poetic prose alternates between quiet actions and internal descriptions, with palpable passages on physical abuse: “Taylor heard the awful hollow crunch and then, like a bottle of champagne popping open, the blood fountained up and sprayed in all directions.”\r
Language is detailed and chiselled, capturing youthful voices and dialect in the third-person narrator that alternates between Taylor and Lily’s point of view. “Taylor imagined that inside Lily was some kind of glowing core of strength made of a rare outer-space metal that radiated power into all her veins and muscles.” Lily sees that “Devon sucked up Taylor’s power like she was his battery, and he recharged by draining her away.”\r
Vivid and wrenching, the themes of violence, abuse and loss are depicted unflinchingly here, yet Lily and Taylor’s resilience carries them forward.""" ;
