ns2:Bookd258f379-ecd0-4861-b95f-786d5fad7895 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Claire A. Nivola" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54107" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2008"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:MacMilan ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Based on true events, this book tells the uplifting story of Wangari Maathai, founder of the Green Belt Movement and winner of the 2004 Nobel Peace Prize. Before leaving for America to study biology at college, Wangari grew up in the Highlands of Kenya, when farmers were still able to live off their fertile land.  By the time she returned, only five years later, she found the Kenyans and their land impoverished. The trees had been cut, making room for large plantations, and locals were no longer able to sustain themselves independently.\r
\r
Rather than pointing the finger, Wangari proposed a brilliant solution that empowered the people: she showed them how to collect seeds from the remaining trees, and plant new ones.\r
\r
The author’s note at the back provides additional biographical and historical information to spawn discussion on this powerful example of female leadership. Luminous, pointillist-style watercolour illustrations evoke the people’s noble efforts to salvage their sacred land. Meanwhile, lyrical text sings with Wangari’s wisdom: “‘When the soil is exposed,’ Wangari tells us ‘it is crying out for help, it is naked and needs to be clothed ….’”\r
\r
Readers are made aware of the issue of sustainability and, like Wangari, learn to consider the world beyond themselves. “‘When we see we are part of the problem,’ she said, ‘we can become part of the solution.’” The value of taking charge of your own future by caring for the environment is clear.""" ;
    ns2:title "Planting the Trees of Kenya: The Story of Wangari Maathai" ;
