ns2:Bookde24ac63-62f8-43cd-ba78-124d0de464ad a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Monique Gray Smith" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55862" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Orca Book Publishers"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Narrated in the first person, this simple yet potent reflection on kindness—for one another as well as for animals and the Earth’s resources—is filled with stylish and richly coloured illustrations. “I am kind” is the positive refrain in this introduction to good practices, from a child’s perspective: “I am kind when I help my family;” “I am kind when I share with my friends;” “I am kind when I take my dog for an extra long walk.” \r
Illustrations use rich, deep colours and eye-catching details to depict skillful compositions of children and their families that reflect the direct simplicity of the language. One image shows a child in her mother’s arms as they gather berries. Strong, basic shapes represent their hair and t-shirts, contrasting with the highly detailed berries and leaves. The mother’s beaded earrings pop with the same tone as the berries in the bushes. “I am kind when I only take from the earth what I need.” Another image shows a child asleep in her darkened bedroom; her closed eyes contrast with the dot-sized eyes of her stuffed bear, peering at the reader from under the quilt. The bed, bookshelf and night table are portrayed in simple colour-block forms, while the child’s moccasins, basket, drum and dream catcher are rendered in exquisite detail. “I am kind when I take care of myself and get a good night’s sleep.” \r
The story’s message gradually broadens from actions to underlying emotions—and the natural reciprocity that occurs when we are good to one another: “I feel loved when my elders are kind to me;” “I feel grateful when the earth is kind to me.” This message is emphasized in a final image depicting a circle-gathering of women, children and a dog (comfortably lounging, nose to tail). The lush green of the ground is specked with stylized flowers, as a bird flies through clear skies: “When we are kind, we remember we are all related.” The back cover urges reader introspection and discussion, asking, “What does kindness mean to you?”""" ;
    ns2:title "When We Are Kind" ;
