ns2:Booke015b24a-0014-4ce2-8d0c-a4b08dcee678 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Holly M. McGhee" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56220" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "G.P. Putnam's Sons"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Watching the world through the television news, a child wishes to help ease the anger, hatred and fear she sees. Her papa takes her for a subway ride and is courteous to all the different people they meet. Her mama takes her to the specialty grocery, where they buy food from different lands. Then the girl goes out by herself, to walk the dog: she invites the neighbour’s boy to join her; together, they welcome a smaller child into their games at the park. By being open, considerate and friendly, the girl makes her world a better place for everyone. \r
A real-world antidote to the anxiety propagated by news media is offered in this tale of one family’s approach to respectful urban living: “Waiting there on the platform, her papa tipped his hat to those he met. So, the little girl did, too.” Minimalist illustrations use bold lines and pastel-hued fills to depict the multicultural family and their diverse neighbourhood. One scene shows a delicious array of cakes and pastries from the shop, “Import Corner of the World.” “Because one person doesn’t represent a family. Or a race or the people of a land.” As their tiny dog waits in the doorway, the girl and her mother converse with the shopkeeper: \r
A double-page spread features two spot images of open doorways: the girl walks through one (leading her dog on her first solo-foray into the world); on the facing page, the neighbour’s son pokes his head through the other. The language echoes the book’s message of harmony: “When the little girl opened the door, the boy across the hall opened his door, too.” While the story addresses the simple joys of community life: “The girl, the boy and the dog were happy to be out,” images show a walk through the park and making chalk drawings with a smaller child. “Brave gentle, strong—and kind… to one another and all living things”. The ripple-effect of positivity is depicted in a final spread, as doors open all around, releasing children and their families to come out and join in the drawing activity: “Your part matters, too.”""" ;
