    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Tundra_Books ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Alternating chapters from the perspectives of 13-year-old Stewart and 14-year-old Ashley, convey this funny and profound story about the creation of a blended family.\r
Both characters are insightful and entertaining narrators. Ashley struggles to keep her picture-perfect image from cracking: “I agonize a lot over whether or not I’m gayist. I mean, on the one hand, we have an LGBT club at our school and I’m totally cool with that, even if I’ve been known to call the president a Tragic behind hisher back.”\r
Meanwhile Stewart tries to make friends without getting creamed: “It’s true that she only laughed a little bit. And it’s true that she said ‘You’re an odd duck.’ But she didn’t say it in a mean voice.… So, as is clear on my chart, that part of the day was a highlight.”\r
The complications of life in a blended family are conveyed with wit and nuance, through authentic characters. Credible events show compromise and growth—and are enriched by backstories of the teens’ previous families. This extremely satisfying novel expertly interweaves the narrators’ viewpoints, with conflict gradually shifting to cooperation. Under pressure from a school sociopath, and the loss of the family cat, Stewart and Ashley’s alliance becomes one of mutual affection and respect, supported within a strong familial web.""" ;
