    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """A sense of peaceful nostalgia permeates this story about a hangout beloved by children, in a desert town, decades ago. Eloquent details convey the total engagement of the youngsters. Everyone in Roxaboxen can drive (“Anna May, quiet little Anna May, was always speeding—you’d think she liked to go to jail”), and ride a horse (“There were no speed limits for horses”).\r
The pretend town grows, with stones mapping out streets, houses and shops. This is fantasy play of the homiest kind. Illustrations skillfully reflect the quiet tone of the story. Textural pastel effects depict quaint child-characters in big desert landscapes. One pretty spread of cool blue and gray shows a war game—boys against girls—being fought with “whirling swords of ocotillo.” Another uses the glowing colours of a desert evening to depict a fenced-in patch, blooming with catci: a cemetery, “in case anyone died.”\r
In the end, the theme of fond, lasting memories becomes explicit when one of the players returns to the hill as an old woman. “Because none of them ever forgot Roxaboxen. Not one of them ever forgot.”""" ;
