    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Laurence King Publishing"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Ingenious sculptural illustrations provide ample counting opportunities through wordless scenes that represent numbers from 1 to 10. Each spread is constructed entirely of papers in a variety of colours and textures—trimmed, stacked and folded—for a 3D, diorama-like effect.\r
Pretty scenes offer much for the eye to explore. Numbers are represented in numeral form, with many examples of the same quantity in each image. In the spread dedicated to “2,” two Japanese-style teahouses sit on two hills, joined by the arc of a traditional wooden bridge. Birds, goldfish, flowers—even the styles of tree foliage—are all found in pairs throughout the scene.\r
Houses proliferate as the counting continues: five tree houses in a forest, a row of six Victorian houses, a village of eight South African Ndebele houses. Plants, creatures and decorative motifs provide a wealth of counting practice. In the end, 10 narrow town houses of the Netherlands line a canal that’s home to 10 ducks. 10 bicycles are parked in the street. 10 birch trees sport 10 leaves each, and 10 potted plants ((tulips, of course) decorate the frontage. Illustrated end material discusses the different types of architecture depicted throughout the book.""" ;
