ns2:Bookf0a378da-e737-4022-862e-420519393f89 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Slavia Roy & Miki Miki" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56881" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Tradewind Books"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book tells the heartwarming story, based on true events, of a small community’s resourcefulness and care for all living things. Off the shore of the small town of Seal Cove in Newfoundland, a small pod of white-beaked dolphins became trapped in the ice one winter. Told through the first-person point of view of a young girl, Nicole, the narrative recounts the dolphins’ haunting cries, which keep the whole village up at night, and the courageous rescue efforts of two men—Nicole’s older brothers in the story—who open up a channel in the ice to free the animals. Two of the dolphins escape, but a third, too weak to swim, needs help. One of the men, Aaron, stays in the water in his survival suit, embracing the dolphin and keeping them both afloat, until the rescuers harness it and lead it out to the open sea, where the dolphin comes to life and swims repeatedly back to the boat—“the dolphin is thanking them for saving her life.” The story subtly touches on the importance of doing the right thing in caring for any animal in distress, and the moving intimacy between two species. The book concludes with an afterword on white-beaked dolphins by a biologist and a note from the author detailing the true events that inspired the book. \r
\r
Through shapes and blocks of colour, the illustrations juxtapose a sense of the dream-like landscape in the isolated coastal outpost. The ice and the open water are contrasted in dark grey and beige, while the dolphins are outlined in soft shapes with cut-outs to show the flank, belly, and beak. From the men’s red survival suits to Nicole’s burgundy coat and green boots, the humans create spots of colour against the snowy winter shores, over which a pale sun shines weakly. The relationship with non-human animals is evoked elsewhere in the story, notably through the presence of Nicole’s pet dog. The spot and one-page illustrations and frequent two-page spreads mimic the pace and tone of the narrative, from anguish and alarm to compassion, adrenaline and relief.""" ;
