ns2:Bookf12bfb90-2f7c-489a-aca2-f79f62a6e565 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Wes Moore" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54143" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns2:reviewBody """As soon as Elijah picked up a ball, energy began to course and surge through his body, all electric and powerful, muscle fibers burning and twitching with the promise of...of what? Sixteen-year-old Elijah's desire to prove himself on the basketball court is tangled up with a different dream: to prove himself to his father, who left when he was two. While Elijah shares a close relationship with his hardworking mother and his two best friends, he still dreams of looking up from the court to see his dad watching him from the bleachers. \r
This story unfolds in two- to five-page chapters. The inner-city Baltimore setting is brought to life in short descriptions. Much of the rich dialogue is in African American vernacular English. “I heard the kid got iced by some gangbanger,” says a friend of Elijah's, about a shooting. A high-five is slapping skin, shoes are kicks, and when Elijah worries, he's bugging.\r
 For Elijah, making decisions is much simpler on the basketball court than it is in life. A kid from Elijah's school is shot and killed by a gang member, and then his three-on-three basketball team receives a suspicious sponsorship offer for an upcoming tournament. Meanwhile, he finds unlikely allies in Banks, a beer-drinking, cigar-smoking army vet, and his college-bound daughter. Elijah's team's eventual refusal to wear uniforms bearing gang insignia has stupefying consequences: one of his best friends is murdered. Elijah must choose between revenge and his own future on the court.""" ;
