ns2:Bookf73e2570-2f6d-46b0-b037-d2584176a895 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Christopher Silas Neil" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56885" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This picture book narrates the woes of a cat that doesn’t know what to eat. While “dogs eat dog food” and “fish eat fish food,” this striped yellow house cat is a picky eater: “I will NOT eat cat food. It’s dry and dull and not very yummy.” The cat sets out on a journey to interview other species and ask what they eat. A turtle, a fox, a chimpanzee, a lion, an elephant and a whale all volunteer their own food preferences, but each one comes with a caveat: “But I must warn you,” says each animal, pointing out a flaw in their prey or plant. After each disappointment, the cat asks the next animal for a food suggestion that avoids the previous animals’ warnings, and the accrual and repetition reinforces vocabulary and acts as a refrain. By the time the cat gets to the whale, “I’m really hungry and searching for something yummy to eat that doesn’t wiggle, bounce, or bite and that isn’t too big, too dry, or too boring.” (The whale’s nutritional option ends up being too hard to pronounce.) Finally, the cat encounters a mouse, which is also wondering what to eat. As the cat contemplates the mouse, it suddenly figures out its own nutritional preferences, though it says to the mouse, in a comically thrilling ending, “I must warn you….” \r
\r
The mixed-media illustrations are representative and fun, showing the slightly anthropomorphized yellow cat approaching various animals, however unlikely their presence. The single- and double-page spreads alternately face the short, large text and are placed above it, first for the cat to ask the animal, and then depicting each particular species in their habitat and eating their typical food. The images also make use of comparison and shapes, showing, for instance, the relatively tiny cat speaking to an elephant’s humongous back foot and dangling tail. The colours are sometimes unrealistic—a pink fox, a red lion—and the detailed landscapes that follow the introduction of each species provide rich and satisfying context.""" ;
    ns2:title "I Won’t Eat That" ;
