ns2:Bookf85b31db-fc38-44c0-bff1-d976ffe15578 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "De Nichols" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56594" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Big Picture Press – Candlewick Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This richly illustrated book about protest art functions as historical lesson, explanation, and inspiration. The four chapters touch on the role of art in social movements, the history and visual components of protest art, student movements, different forms of protest and the influence of technology. The narrative is anchored by the author’s formative experiences during and after the Ferguson Uprising that resulted from the police murder of Michael Brown Jr. From that initial spark, we learn about the communicative, imaginative, and amplifying function of protest art such as that by Ai Weiwei, Banksy and Elizabeth Vega. The extent of the research and information is considerable. For instance, we find out the origins of the peace sign, the clenched fist, rainbows and other symbolic images that have become common cultural currency. We learn the significance of different colours, and we discover what different typefaces can convey. Each chapter concludes with a section entitled “Try This,” which includes suggestions for how young people can get involved in, or even spark, public protest movements. \r
\r
The graphics are extraordinarily varied and compelling, as befits a book that strives to present an overview of protest art. The illustrations, which were created by five different artists, range from realistic ink-and-watercolour sketches of protesters to woodcut-like prints showing the wrinkled brows and resolve of Apartheid activists, to colourful drawings that dismantle the serious absolutes of war and violence. The book also includes extensive examples of protest art by artists such as Keith Haring and Jacob Lawrence. The book itself is intended to feel like a street manual: the covers are heavy cardboard, and the spine is open, with visible folds and sewing.""" ;
    ns2:title "Art of Protest: Creating, Discovering, and Activating Art for your Revolution" ;
