ns2:Bookf874b39c-2f31-4337-a662-568b8650ea81 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Patricia McCormick" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54317" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2016"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:HarperCollins ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This is the true account of Dietrich Bonhoeffer, an unassuming pastor from an aristocratic German family, who searched his soul and decided that “silence in the face of evil is itself evil.” Despite the potential repercussions, he worked tirelessly, speaking against Hitler’s rising power in Germany and later trying desperately to gain the support of churches across Europe as he described the atrocities happening in his country against the Jews.\r
The text handles fact and narrative smoothly, portraying Bonhoeffer as a sensitive dreamer who, as a child, would “watch the clouds scud by overhead, feel the breeze rustle the pine needles in the forest nearby and think.” The text is not complex but offers brief asides of historical context, including timelines, descriptions of laws that were introduced and Hitler’s Mein Kampf, in which he “described what he called ‘the Jewish peril,’ his theory of a Jewish conspiracy to take over the world.”\r
With Mein Kampf replacing the Bible among the clergy, and the university where Bonhoeffer taught saturated in Nazi propaganda, he went undercover, working with others in a plot to kill Hitler. Bonhoeffer was the first person to tell “the outside world what was happening to the Jews of Germany.” Photos and documents enhance the narrative, showing Bonhoeffer as a boy and young man, and finally the Flossenbürg concentration camp where he was hanged. With his wealth and connections, Bonhoeffer could have fled to safety but he persisted in speaking out to counteract the silence of the churches and others in authority, and paid the ultimate price.""" ;
    ns2:title "Plot to Kill Hitler: Dietrich Bonhoeffer: Pastor, Spy, Unlikely Hero" ;
