ns2:Bookf8c266c1-7bb5-4010-8f1e-4d89f27d6cbd a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Muon Thi Van" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56128" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Kids_Can_Press ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Readers are invited to imagine themselves in a variety of situations in these evocative musings on nighttime in the natural world. \r
“If you were night and you heard a frog bellow and another croak, would you hop away quickly? Or would you drum your heart’s desire, too?” \r
Rich vocabulary and imaginative scenarios create this poetic tale of a nighttime ramble: out of the house, through the yard, past the shed (“a racoon rooting and tussling”), by the creek (“a spider scuttle and pull”) and finally into the wild: “would you join the thrilling hunt too?” \r
Detailed, atmospheric scenes use layers of cut and folded paper, which cast shadows and create depth. Readers may pore over the details of images. One spread depicts wildlife at the river: a fish jumps, causing a cut-out “splash” as a bear watches intently. A frog and sprouting mushrooms alike enjoy the hospitality of a decaying log. A moth seems to glow in the moonlight, while high above, an owl scans the action below: “bear snuffling, the snake rustling, the slug munching, the salmon leaping.” The subsequent spread shows a close-up on the owl and its mouse-prey: cut-out blades of grass create an intimidating terrain. \r
As night turns into day, the story’s end draws readers back from a world of hypothetical adventures (“would you stay up to taste a drop of morning dew?”), to the comforts of home and bed: “Or would you close your eyes and let the lightness carry you, too?” A final question invites readers to craft their own nocturnal hypotheticals: “If you were night, what would you do?”""" ;
    ns2:title "If You Were Night" ;
    ns1:isCoupDeCoeur true ;
