ns2:Bookf9eece1b-38e7-43b7-b24c-e914d0aa13c5 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Patrick McDonnell" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55471" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2005"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher "Little, Brown and Company"^^xsd:string ;
    ns2:reviewBody """This installment in the Mutts series is a picture book that takes a somewhat philosophical take on gift-giving and friendship. Mooch the cat wants to give his best friend and neighbour, Earl the dog, a gift but Earl has everything—a bowl, a bed, a chew toy. “What do you get someone who has everything?” Mooch wonders, before coming up with the perfect solution: “Nothing!” What follows is a naive misunderstanding of human idiom: Mooch’s human always says there’s nothing on TV, but the television set’s blathering says otherwise: “as far as Mooch could tell, there was always something on TV.” Doozy and her friends often complain that there’s nothing to do, but they’re constantly playing at something. And Millie claims that there’s nothing to buy in the store, but when Mooch goes shopping he only finds “many, many somethings.” Finally, after some feline meditation, Mooch gives Earl a big box filled with “nothing… but me and you!” and the two pets hug and enjoy each other’s company, which is more important than any thing. \r
\r
The spare ink and watercolour illustrations that have characterized this comic strip since its appearance almost thirty years ago are compelling for young readers as well: the wide white background provides a clear contrast for the simply drawn human and pet interactions. Some pages have no text, such as a two-page spread showing the store Mooch goes to try to buy a nothing, which is crammed with shelves full of parcels, and a string of anonymous silhouettes shopping. The dog and cat adopt human behaviours—gift-giving, shopping, hugging and so forth—but they are resolutely animal in their accoutrements and action, and the details of their bond are simple and touching—Earl wagging his tail, or the two friends sitting on the back of the couch with their paws around each other, looking out the window, with Earl’s belongings—secondary to their friendship—scattered on the floor.""" ;
