ns2:Bookfac5099b-3dd0-45ed-a3c2-ba10701315d6 a ns2:Book ;
    ns2:author "Jill Murray" ;
    ns2:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54839" ;
    ns2:datePublished "2010"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns2:publisher ns2:Doubleday ;
    ns2:reviewBody """Alya is 16 when a producer approaches her after a b-girl performance. She auditions and is accepted into a new Montréal group called EnChantay. The other members of the group, Julie and Angelique, are cruel to her, and though the choreography is easy for her, Alya must learn to sing. While Alya knows she likes girls she has yet to come out to anyone, even herself. \r
\r
Alya is a witty and self-deprecating narrator. She describes the producer as “a man dressed like every Hollywood tabloid skeez in recent history stapled together.” Her observations are honest and sharp as she recounts her struggles to fit in: “Julie and Angelique stared at each other across the table like they were trying to communicate using only their eyes, so they wouldn’t have to talk to me.” \r
\r
When Alya agrees to help Angelique with her dancing, they become friends. Alya develops feelings for her, which leads to a drunken kiss after their first performance: “a single, clear thought rang out: This is what it’s supposed to feel like. It was exactly like I’d never had the guts to imagine it.” \r
\r
Angelique turns on Alya after that, and Alya becomes disillusioned by the insincerity of the industry: “I loved the spotlight. And because I loved the spotlight I didn’t want it to shine on garbage.” Alya returns to b-girling in her hometown. That’s where she notices a “girl with pixie hair and a tiny rainbow pin” watching her. With newfound confidence, Alya heads over to introduce herself.""" ;
