    ns2:reviewBody """What if you could help secret wishes come true? When Ava finds a magic pencil that answers every question, that is one thing she and her best friend, Sophie, use it for.\r
Told in the third person, this well-written tale strikes the perfect balance between explaining and letting readers figure things out for themselves. The plot moves forward at a nice pace, with plenty of surprising and lively details. It presents a realistic depiction of anxiety, which plays a strong role in Ava’s life. Even if there is no final solution, she does find ways to deal with her anxiety, such as playing the saxophone.\r
Although Ava and Sophie use the pencil to find out all sorts of things, including classmates’ secrets and information about crushes, Ava also learns that even helping people has its risks. “Because what if she played that song and grandpa didn’t like it at all and he was even grumpier? What if Mrs. Grabowski cried again? What if all the old people hated Ava’s song and they started throwing cookies and cups of warm lemonade at her …?”\r
Ava learns a difficult lesson: just because you know something doesn’t mean you have control over it. She learns to be brave in her own way and ultimately understands a little more about the mysteries of life, death, family and friends.""" ;
